<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Minister on Convertibility of Rupee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Commerce Minister
Ishaq Dar said today his country will not make its currency of
rupee convertible until it acquires a position of healthy and
growing foreign reserves.
</P>
<P>
In a television interview, Ishaq said that as rich foreign
exchange reserves were essential for the convertibility of the
Pakistani currency, Pakistan needs to have its foreign exchange
reserves something to the tune of over 4 to 5 billion U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
"This is a very natural requirement because wherever in the
world there is a free market in the currency. In order to
stabilize the demand and supply, the central bank of a country
needs to intervene," he said.
</P>
<P>
"So, in order to avoid any speculative moves and exploitation
of the situation by profiteers after the convertibility of the
rupee, a backing of good foreign exchange reserves is required,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Answering a question about the government's concept on rupee
convertibility, he said the original version was one of Prime
Minister Nawaz Sharif who wished to open up the currency as per
the existing practice of many developed countries in the world.
</P>
<P>
"So, the Prime Minister's vision is that we should make rupee
convertible as early as feasible and possible", he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
