<HEADLINE> Nevada, Prehistoric Comet Impact Site: Scientists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, October 21 (Xinhua) -- The Nevada State in the
southwestern United States is believed to be one of the three
sites on Earth where prehistoric comet impacts occurred, U.S.
scientists said.
</P>
<P>
A comet at about two-thirds of a mile in diameter hit 90 miles
north of Las Vegas near a town called Alamo about 370 million
years ago, making the region, then an ocean 30 feet deep, 10 times
deeper and the crater extending out 120 miles, they said.
</P>
<P>
Geologist Charles Sandberg of the U.S. Geological Survey,
Denver, presented forms of evidence to judge his conclusion to a
Geological Society of America meeting in Salt Lake City Monday,
USA Today reported.
</P>
<P>
Fossilized tree remains dated to the period suggest that the
comet started forest fires in nearby Wyoming, he added.
</P>
<P>
Sandberg showed several forms of evidence found at the area,
including "shocked" quartz grains, deposits of iridium and
carbonate spherules that form in a superheated cloud after
limestone is pulverized.
</P>
<P>
Scientists believe that giant slabs of rock around Alamo which
were left twisted and lying at angles are also evidence of a
blast.
</P>
<P>
They said during the impact time, called the Devonian period,
80 percent to 90 percent of Earth surface was covered by water. As
a result of three impacts, including this one, over 70 percent of
life on Earth was destroyed.
</P>
<P>
Two other impacts are believed to have taken place a few
million years apart in Belgium and Sweden. 
</P>
</TEXT>
