<HEADLINE> Africa Gets Small Share in World Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Africa got a small share last
year in the global Foreign Direct Investments (FDI) despite
increased FDI in other regions of the world.
</P>
<P>
FDI inflows into Africa were last year less than the record
level of 5.8 billion U.S. Dollars as Africa got the lowest level
of FDI since early 1994, according to a report from the United
Nations Conference on Trade and Development (UNCTAD).
</P>
<P>
Africa's oil producing countries accounted for about 70
percent of the total direct inflows. Nigeria, being by far the
largest recipient of FDI, got 1.7 billion Dollars in 1996
followed by Egypt which got 740 million Dollars.
</P>
<P>
Africa's share of FDI inflows from developed countries was
less than 4 percent during the period under review, representing
the lowest share since early 1980, indicating that the region is
not participating in the global FDI boom.
</P>
<P>
The UNCTAD report, however, said that Africa can still expect
better prospects of inflows of FDI following recent development
of reduction in internal conflicts, the expected economic
recovery and improved macro-economic performance.
</P>
<P>
The World Investment Report 1997 said the potential of South
Africa's economy is a key factor in determining FDI prospects for
parts of sub-Saharan Africa as direct investment by South African
firms could play a crucial role in the development of neighboring
economies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
