<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: "One Country, Two Systems" and China's Reunification (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 21 (Xinhua) -- The concept of "one country,
two systems", a major component of Deng Xiaoping Theory, was used
to solve Hong Kong and Macao issues, and will be also the
guideline for solving the Taiwan issue which is crucial to the
ultimate reunification of China and the revitalization of the
Chinese nation.
</P>
<P>
The concept of "one country, two system" embodies the
principles of safeguarding China's sovereignty while achieving
national reunification. The highly flexible concept gives full
consideration to both history and reality.
</P>
<P>
"One country, two systems", based on the precondition of
reunification, requires China to adhere to socialism, with
Hong Kong, Macao and Taiwan retaining their capitalist system for
a long period of time.
</P>
<P>
Deng Xiaoping's concept is by no means a measure creating an
impediment, but is instead a major strategy.
</P>
<P>
Implementation of "one country, two systems" is conducive to
China's reunification and world peace and development. The
realization of reunification is the common aspiration of the
Chinese people as a whole, including people from the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region (SAR), Taiwan, Macao and overseas
Chinese.
</P>
<P>
Successful implementation of the concept in Hong Kong has
proven that the format is practical and has a bright future.
</P>
<P>
Resolving the Taiwan issue is one of China's major priorities
after solving the issues of Kong Hong and Macao. President Jiang
Zemin introduced his eight-point proposal in 1995 setting forth
the basic principles of the Communist Party of China for solving
the Taiwan issue.
</P>
<P>
The main points of Jiang's proposal follow:
</P>
<P>
First, adherence to the "one China" principle. Adherence to the
principle is the basis and primary condition for China's
reunification. The core of "peaceful reunification", "one country,
two systems" and the eight-point proposal centers on the fact that
China's sovereignty and territory should be reunified.
</P>
<P>
Despite the fact that the two sides of the Taiwan Straits are
not as yet reunified, Taiwan is nonetheless an unseparable part of
the People's Republic of China, with the latter having
indisputable sovereignty over the former.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, China resolutely opposes those who advocate "split
sovereignty, separate governments" and claim that the two sides
are equal political entities. All activities carried out with a
view towards creating "two Chinas", or "one China, one Taiwan" are
doomed to failure.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971022.0007 </DOCNO>
