<HEADLINE> Muslim Extremists Kill Six in Southern Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Six people were killed and
scores of others wounded today in a southern Philippine province
when a group of heavily armed men attacked a coconut cooperative,
local television reports said.
</P>
<P>
The gunmen, believed to be members of the Muslim extremist Abu
Sayyaf group, fired at a crowd of villagers in Lantawan town,
Basilan province, and fled immediately after the carnage, the Sky
Cable television reported.
</P>
<P>
The reports said the authorities had so far failed to determine
the motive for the massacre.
</P>
<P>
The Abu Sayyaf, which is notorious for robberies, kidnappings
and harassment of villagers, has been pursued hard by the military
for abducting and killing eight villagers early this month.
</P>
<P>
The extremist group and the Moro Islamic Liberation Front
(MILF) are the two remaining Muslim rebel forces still fighting
the government.
</P>
<P>
The MILF began peace talks with the government early this year,
but the Abu Sayyaf has shunned peace negotiations with Manila.
</P>
<P>
The mainstream Moro National Liberation Front (MNLF) signed a
peace agreement with the government in September 1996.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971022.0008 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: "One Country, Two Systems" and China's Reunification (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Second, striving for reunification. Both sides of the Taiwan
Straits belong to the Chinese nation, and thus achieving
reunification through peaceful means and realizing national
revitalization will not only benefit people across the Straits,
but will also promote peace and development in Asia and the world
as a whole.
</P>
<P>
Reunification is the common aspiration of all Chinese people
and is also welcomed by the international community.
</P>
<P>
However, the development of separatism in Taiwan and the
interference of foreign forces has prevented the People's Republic
of China from committing itself the abandonment of the use of
force. The stance is in no way directed at the people of Taiwan,
but instead at foreign forces meddling in the issue and at the
attempting to achieve "Taiwan independence".
</P>
<P>
Third, promoting peaceful reunification through
negotiations. Reunification will finally be achieved through
proper means. Deng Xiaoping once suggested that the Communist
Party and the Kuomintang hold talks on a equal footing -- the
third cooperation of CPC and the KMT in Chinese history.
</P>
<P>
Jiang Zemin's report during the CPC 15th National Congress once
again called for political negotiations between the two sides at
the earlist possible date.
</P>
<P>
The first step, according to Jiang, will require the two sides
to hold talks designed to "formally end hostilities under the
principle of one China" and reach an agreement. The two sides
should commit themselves to certain obligations and proceed from
the standpoint of safeguarding the integrity of China's
sovereignty and territory, and draft plans for the future
development of relations between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
The problem of reunification must be solved by the Chinese
people from both sides of the Taiwan straits, Jiang said. He
called to ideas and suggestions conducive to the reunification
effort.
</P>
</TEXT>
