<BODY>
<HEADLINE> African Exporters Urged to Improve Packaging </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, October 21 (Xinhua) -- African companies need to
improve the packaging of their products if they are to
effectively compete with imported goods, exhibitors at Zimbabwe's
packaging and printing exhibition said today.
</P>
<P>
At the beginning of the three-day exhibition in Bulawayo,
Zimbabwe's second largest city, most exhibitors said other
countries had advanced ways of packaging their goods which most
African countries still had to catch up with.
</P>
<P>
Although most products such as coffee were grown locally,
Africans failed to market them because they lacked the ability to
package them attractively, they said.
</P>
<P>
''African products can penetrate the European market with good
packaging because that alone can sell a product,'' said Pankaj
Patel, Director of the Kenyan-based Prudential Printers.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwean companies, however, expressed optimism that the
situation has been changing as they are constantly researching to
improve their packaging.
</P>
<P>
Paul Denton, an export executive with the locally-based Treger
Plastics, said one of the ways of doing this was through constant
participation in international fairs and conferences.
</P>
<P>
Organizer of the exhibition, Zimbabwe International Trade Fair
said 20 foreign companies and 100 local firms were attending the
exhibition which is aimed at promoting the printing and packaging
industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
