<HEADLINE> Shanghai Becomes Aging City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Nearly one-fifth of Shanghai's
population, or 2.31 million people, were aged above 60 at the end
of last year.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai is expecting the rate of old people to further rise,
said Feng Guishan, Director of the Municipal Aging Population
Committee, at a three-day international seminar on aging
population which was opened in this largest city of China today.
</P>
<P>
Over 200 population experts from a dozen countries and regions,
including the United States, Japan, Canada and China will share
their views on various problems concerning the aged population.
</P>
<P>
To date, the city has set up over 400 old people's homes with
more than 12,000 beds. Meanwhile, more than 640,000 local people
have volunteered to assist poor or lonely old people, Feng said,
introducing Shanghai's experience in caring the old to other
participants.
</P>
<P>
The city government also provides money and daily necessities
to these needy elders, he told the seminar.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
