<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Protests Turkish Violation of Airspace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus has strongly protested
to the United Nations against recent violations of its sovereign
airspace and the Nicosia Flight Information Region (FIR) by
Turkish military aircraft, Cyprus News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
The protest was contained in a letter addressed to the 52nd
U.N. General Assembly and the Security Council by Cypriot
Permanent Representative to the U.N., Nicos Agathocleous,
according to the agency.
</P>
<P>
Agathocleous stressed in his letter that "these highly
provocative and aggressive actions of Turkey cause serious concern
and heighten tension in Cyprus."
</P>
<P>
He pointed out between September 30 to October 14, "an
alarmingly increasing number" of violations of Cyprus' airspace
and of the Nicosia FIR by military aircraft of the Turkish air
force took place.
</P>
<P>
He cited a detailed list of all violations by Turkish military
aircraft including F-16 fighters and RF-4 reconnaissance planes.
</P>
<P>
"Such provocative actions by Turkey, which are continuing, are
in contravention of the provisions of the Security Council
resolutions on Cyprus," the Cypriot diplomat noted.
</P>
<P>
The letter pointed out that such overflights increase political
tension on the island and undermine efforts toward achieving a
final settlement to the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus held a military exercise code-named "Nikiforos '97"
from October 10 to 14, with the participation of Greek air and
naval forces.
</P>
<P>
Turkey responded with repeated violations of Cypriot and Greek
airspace and a plan of military exercises in northern Cyprus next
month.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops and took over the northern third of the island following a
failed coup by Greek Cypriots seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus problem has remained unsolved despite the U.N. and
international community's peace efforts for the past 23 year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
