<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Meets Leaders of Duma Factions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
today met parliamentary factions leaders in the Kremlin in an
effort to dissuade Russia's leftist opposition from a censure vote
on the cabinet, the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin said after the meeting that the no-confidence motion on
the government scheduled for Wednesday's session of the State
Duma, or the lower house of parliament, will decide "whether the
political stability continues in the country or not."
</P>
<P>
Interfax noted that the president will send the State Duma a
message to show support to the issues raised earlier by the
leaders of the Communist Party faction, the Popular Rule and
Agrarian parliamentary groups.
</P>
<P>
As for today's meeting, Yeltsin's spokesman Sergei
Yastrzhembsky said the president is satisfied with the meeting,
describing it as "productive."
</P>
<P>
Communist Party leader Gennady Zyuganov is also reported to be
satisfied with the meeting.
</P>
<P>
"The conversation was fruitful and we were met half way on
practically all matters which the left-wing opposition put
forward," Zyuganov was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Alexander Shokhin, leader of Our Home Is Russia faction, said
the left guarantees to withdraw its back of the no-confidence
motion.
</P>
<P>
Only leader of Yabloko faction, Grigory Yavlinsky, insisted his
support to the no-confidence motion, if it is put to vote on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Duma Speaker Gennady Seleznev predicted that after
the president's meeting with Duma factions leaders, the
no-confidence motion is likely to be dropped from the agenda of
Wednesday's Duma session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
