<DOCNO> XIE19971022.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Chief Urges Action to Reduce Global Hunger by </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 21 (Xinhua) -- UN Secretary-General
Kofi Annan today called on all states to take actions to reduce
the global hunger by half by the year 2015.
</P>
<P>
Addressing at a special ceremony to mark the World Food Day,
the secretary-general said that 800 million people in the world
were chronically hungry, which represented roughly one out of
every seven people on earth and included more than 200 million
children under the age of five.
</P>
<P>
The UN chief said millions more were plagued by blindness,
retarded growth and other ailments related to hunger and
malnutrition, and by deliberating effects of diets lacking in
essential vitamins and minerals. Twenty-nine countries, mostly in
Africa, were experiencing food emergencies.
</P>
<P>
Annan said on the threshold of a new century, the age-old
problem of hunger was tragically widespread. As long as such
suffering was allowed to continue, the hopes for an era of
enduring peace and sustainable development would go unfulfilled.
</P>
<P>
He said this year's World Food Day theme "Investing in Food
Security" highlighted the question of resources. Recent years had
not only seen a decline in official development assistance, but
also a drop in agriculture's share of aid. Moreover, countries
most threatened by food insecurity were not investing enough in
the agricultural sector or in the rural economy.
</P>
<P>
The secretary-general said investment was not just a question
of building irrigation system, roads and other infrastructure.
Investment in human resources, and particularly in the education
of women and girls, was just as vital. It was by now common wisdom
that investment in the education of women and girls had the
highest rate of return of any type of investment in development.
</P>
<P>
Annan said that at last November's World Food Summit in Rome,
world leaders pledged to reduce the number of hungry and
malnourished people by half by the year 2015. That was a practical
and attainable target. He called on the governments to rise to
this challenge and encouraged the partnership of private sector
and civil society in this effort.
</P>
<P>
Annan said the United Nations, for its part, had worked since
its inception to help break the vicious circle of hunger,
malnutrition and poverty. The Food and Agriculture Organization,
along with the World Food Program and the International Fund for
Agricultural Development, together with the World Bank, the United
Nations Development Program, the United Nations Children's Fund
and the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees, had all
been deeply involved. Today in the spirit of United Nations
reform, each had taken steps to improve its effectiveness and
coordination.
</P>
<P>
Annan stressed the world had enough food. What it lacked was
the political will to ensure that all people had access to this
bounty, that all people enjoyed food security. 
</P>
