<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Protection of Three Gorges Cultural Relics Well Underway </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, October 21 (Xinhua) -- A large group of Chinese
archeologists are working hard to rescue and protect cultural
relics affected by the Three Gorges Project.
</P>
<P>
A recent survey showed that some 1,280 cultural relics sites
have been discovered in areas near the Three Gorges Dam, China's
largest water conservancy project on the Yangtze River which will
be dammed early next month.
</P>
<P>
The 590 buried and 293 above ground cultural relics sites in
areas near the municipality of Chongqing which will be submerged
account for over two thirds of the total number of cultural relics
in the Three Gorges area.
</P>
<P>
Archeologists noted that their work over the next 12 years will
proceed in accordance with the progress of the Three Gorges
Project.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, work for the remainder of this year will focus on the
32 cultural relics near Wushan County and Fuling
city. Archeologists working in the areas expect to record
breakthrough in prehistoric studies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
