<DOCNO> XIE19971022.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Economists on Continued Weakness of SE Asian Currencies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Although speculative pressures
were behind the initial depreciation of Southeast Asian
currencies, substantial short-term foreign debts, increased demand
for foreign exchanges and lack of confidence have played a role in
the currencies' continued fall.
</P>
<P>
Explaining the reasons behind the continued weakness of
Southeast Asian currencies, World Bank economists Amar
Battacharya, Stijn Claessens and Leonardo Hernadez said
substantial short-term external liabilities of financial
institutions and corporates, the sharp reduction in external
financing and unwillingness among foreign investors to roll-over
short-term loans have resulted in increased net outflow from the
region.
</P>
<P>
In a paper presented to a meeting on Asia's economic outlook
here, they said there has been increased demand for foreign
exchange as many banks and financial institutions try to cover
open positions in anticipation of further depreciation and
currency volatility.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investors, especially equity fund managers, have been
adopting a wait-and-see approach and are withholding new
investments, because they lack confidence in economic fundamentals
and policy measures of Southeast Asian countries, the economists
said.
</P>
<P>
"These three factors have created perceptions of further
currency declines, thus increasing incentives for buying foreign
exchange today," they said.
</P>
<P>
Since early July, the currencies of Singapore, Thailand,
Philippines, Malaysia and Indonesia have depreciated between 10
percent to over 30 percent respectively. Economists say the
currency crisis could last another several months.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971022.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Private Firms Invited to Join in SADC Drought </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, October 21 (Xinhua) -- The 14-member Southern African
Development Community (SADC) intends to actively involve the
private sector in its proposed multi-million Dollars drought
mitigation program, an SADC official said today.
</P>
<P>
The fund would assist drought prone countries in the region,
which have experienced two poor agricultural seasons in the last
five years.
</P>
<P>
Reginald Mugwara, the SADC food security sector coordinator
noted that his sector and the Development Bank of Southern Africa
are given a task to negotiate with, among others, the World Bank
and the European Union to see what role the private sector would
play.
</P>
<P>
"By the end of the year negotiations with the World Bank will
begin," Mugwara told the Zimbabwe News Agency, adding that the
initial 30 million U.S. Dollars proposed would have to be
reviewed as well as various other details pertaining to the fund.
</P>
<P>
A workshop was held last year in Harare where each country
presented a project proposal of a nutrition and information
system needed to identify vulnerable groups.
</P>
<P>
The final document from these proposals would assist in
determining the optimum level of the financial facility.
</P>
<P>
There would also be need to look at control measures of the
fund, as well as legal procedures governing its operations,
Mugwara added.
</P>
<P>
Seed money would come from governments and non-governmental
organizations, and the fund would not be a welfare scheme as
borrowing would be at concessionary interest rates to encourage
countries to utilize it.
</P>
<P>
During the inception stages of the fund, it was expected to
finance maize purchases and would be expanded when its capital
base has increased to purchase other corps, Mugwara explained.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
