<HEADLINE> LPC on Minimum Wage Fact Finding Tour in Scotland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 21 (Xinhua) -- The Low Pay Commission has been
in Scotland today to gather information on the likely impact of
the minimum wage in Scotland, according to an announcement from
the commission.
</P>
<P>
During the day the commission met a wide range of people --
employers, employees, voluntary organizations, low paid and
unemployed people -- to hear their views on what effect a national
minimum wage might have on them.
</P>
<P>
Questions asked include: What should be included in the minimum
wage --tips, bonuses, overtime? Should there be different rates
for people between the ages of 16-25? What will the minimum wage
mean for particular business and voluntary sectors?
</P>
<P>
The commission said it had already written to over 600
organizations. Today's visit is the first of a series the
commission will make across Britain to meet people and gather the
evidence they need on which to base their recommendation on the
minimum wage to the Labor government.
</P>
<P>
Georte Bain, chairman of the Low Pay Commission, said, "We have
to recommend to the prime minister an initial rate for the minimum
wage that will apply in every sector of the economy right across
the United Kingdom."
</P>
<P>
"Therefore it is important that we visit all parts of the
United Kingdom... so we can find out what effect the minimum wage
might have," he added.
</P>
<P>
The Low Pay Commission is an independent advisory body set up
to recommend to the prime minister the initial level at which the
National Minimum Wage might be set. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
