<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-21 16:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ross Arranges Meeting Between Arafat, Mordechai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Amid reports of some
progress in the Israeli-Palestinian talks, U.S. peace envoy
Dennis Ross will host later today a meeting between Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat and Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak
Mordechai.
</P>
<P>
The Arafat-Mordechai meeting is to be held at the Erez
Checkpoint between Israel and the Gaza Strip. Ross arranged the
meeting in a bid to push the two sides to wrap up an agreement
on opening the Gaza airport in Dahaniya by resolving the dispute
over security matters.
</P>
<P>
Ross held a third meeting here with Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu this afternoon after he participated in a
committee-level meeting held in Tel Aviv by Israeli and
Palestinian negotiators. Attending the Tel Aviv meeting were
Israeli Cabinet Secretary Danny Naveh, Foreign Ministry's adviser
Yaacov Bardugo and senior Palestinian negotiators Saeb Erekat
and Hasan Asfour.
</P>
<P>
Erekat said after the meeting that Ross demanded for progress
in the talks despite Israeli positions. He added the Palestinian
National Authority (PNA) does not have trust and confidence in
the current Israeli government.
</P>
<P>
In another related development, Palestinian negotiator Jamil
Tarifi, who is in charge of civil affairs talks, said progress
was made in increasing the annual residence permits issued for
the reunion of Palestinian families.
</P>
<P>
Under the 1995 peace accord, Israel issues 2,000 residence
permits annually to Palestinians for reunion. Now the PNA is
demanding Israel increase the number to 10,000, a request that
Israel is reportedly considering favorably.
</P>
<P>
The major headway in the Israeli-Palestinian talks seems to
be the negotiations on forging an aviation accord over the Gaza
airport. Israeli officials told local newspapers that
progress was made at the meeting held Monday between Israeli
Foreign Minister David Levy and chief PNA negotiator Mahmoud
Abbas (Abu Mazen) hosted by Ross.
</P>
<P>
The accord reportedly comprises three main categories: entry
into Israeli-controlled air space, customs procedures, and
security arrangements on the ground.
</P>
<P>
Israel and PNA negotiators are on the verge of agreeing on
letting Arafat's helicopter to use the Gaza airport, where the
runway is expected to be available to his private jet soon.
</P>
<P>
The PNA preferred to separate the specific airport
arrangements for Arafat and his family from other terms of the
embryonic accord. Levy sought a "package deal," which would
encompass the crucial security aspects of the airport's
operations.
</P>
<P>
But there are no indication if the two sides have narrowed
their dispute over the issue of security control in the
airport. Israel has maintained that it should be granted
security presence in all entries into the airport, while the PNA
is trying to limit Israel's control.
</P>
<P>
The Arafat-Mordechai meeting is aimed at nailing down details
on allowing Arafat's helicopter to use the Gaza airport as a
good-will gesture by Israel to improve the atmosphere for
advancing the talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971022.0025 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
