<HEADLINE> Italy, Philippines to Enhance Economic Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 21 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines and Italy agreed
today to enhance cooperation between the two countries' small and
medium-sized enterprises, and in the fields of transportation and
telecommunication.
</P>
<P>
Two memoranda of understanding were signed after a meeting
between Philippine President Fidel Ramos and visiting Italian
Prime Minister Romano Prodi here today.
</P>
<P>
Under the memoranda, the two sides will facilitate the economic
cooperation between small and medium-scale firms and enterprises
of the two countries within the framework of the respective laws
and regulations.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also agreed to encourage cooperation in
transportation and telecommunication through the exchange of
skills, information and experiences in these fields.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, the two leaders also discussed ways of
improving bilateral trade which reached nearly 400 million U.S.
dollars in 1996, but relatively small compared to Italy's trade
with other Southeast Asian nations.
</P>
<P>
Prodi, who arrived here from the Indonesian capital of Jakarta,
was on a two-day visit to the country.
</P>
<P>
Manila is the third leg of Prodi's four-nation Asian tour which
has already taken him to Singapore and Indonesia. Prodi will
travel on to Tokyo after his visit here.  
</P>
</TEXT>
