<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Pledges Not to Give Up EU Budget Rebate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 21 (Xinhua) -- The British government has
strongly indicated that it will not give up the country's annual
European Union (EU) budget rebate.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a House of Lords select committee early today,
Britain's Economic Secretary to the Treasury Helen Liddell said,
"That is written in stone, and we will insist that it remains
written in stone."
</P>
<P>
The rebate has put some 20 billion pounds (about 32 billion
U.S. dollars) back into British Treasury coffers over the past 13
years and in 1996-97, it amounted to 2.19 billion pounds (about
3.50 billion dollars), more than half of the country's EU
membership fee.
</P>
<P>
She noted that Britain, even with the rebate, was a net
contributor to the EU budget despite ranking 11th among the 15 EU
member states.
</P>
<P>
"The British government is not prepared to countenance any
change in the abatement structure that exists for the United
Kingdom at the present time," she said.
</P>
<P>
On Germany's proposal to reduce its net EU contribution,
Liddell said that Britain had sympathy with Bonn but it was up to
Germany to ease its own burden by agreeing to slash EU agriculture
subsidies.
</P>
<P>
"The quickest way to get net contributions from Germany down is
for Germany to agree to cut EU agriculture spending," she added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
