<HEADLINE> Singapore to Help Handle Indonesia's Monetary Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Singapore Prime Minister Goh
Chok Tong today agreed to join in the efforts of the International
Monetary Fund (IMF) in helping Indonesia cope with its the current
monetary crisis.
</P>
<P>
"Prime Minister Goh and President Soeharto will instruct their
(respective) apparatuses to explain the agreement," Minister/State
Secretary Moerdiono said following the two leaders' meeting at the
Merdeka Palace.
</P>
<P>
Goh arrived here Monday for a two-day working visit as part of
regular consultations among regional leaders.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Moerdiono said, Soeharto briefed his guest
about the ongoing monetary crisis in the country and the efforts
Indonesia are making to overcome the crisis.
</P>
<P>
The president also briefed Goh about the meeting between
Indonesian officials and an IMF team, he added.
</P>
<P>
The IMF team has been talking with Indonesian officials since
last week for a long-term loan sought by the Indonesian government
to deal with the monetary crisis.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian rupiah, along with other regional currencies,
have been under speculative attacks since the devaluation of the
Thai baht in July. The rupiah has dropped by about 50 percent
against the U.S. dollar since the beginning of this year.
</P>
<P>
Asked whether Singapore will pump in funds, Moerdiono said
officials of the two countries will soon meet on the issue.
</P>
<P>
On progress in the dialogue between Indonesian officials and
the IMF, he said the discussion is approaching the final stage.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, Goh said the policies on market orientations
implemented by the Indonesian government at the start of the
crisis will help Indonesia weather the monetary turmoil.
</P>
<P>
Goh said the loss of confidence on the part of investors had
weakened the rupiah.
</P>
<P>
On the Singapore's planned assistance for Indonesia, Moerdiono
said, it could be in the form of fresh money.  
</P>
</TEXT>
