<HEADLINE> Mozambique to Sell Two Sugar Factories </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, October 21 (Xinhua) -- The Mozambican government will
sell two state-owned sugar making factories, Director of the
National Sugar Association Arnaldo Ribeiro has said.
</P>
<P>
Local press today quoted Ribeiro as saying that a Mauritius
enterprise is now negotiating with the Sena Sugar Company which
has the two plants under it at Marromeu of Sofala province and at
Luabo of Zambazia province respectively.
</P>
<P>
Damaged during the civil war, the two factories would be
rehabilitated with a capital of 90 million U.S. Dollars, starting
to planting sugarcanes after levelling the fields next year.
</P>
<P>
At the first stage, the two factories need 2,000 farm hands,
and by 2005, they will need about 5,000 laborers to restore its
best capacity of turning out 120,000 tons of sugar annually, the
director said.
</P>
<P>
Apart from Mauritius, Malaysia and Cuba are also bidding for
the purchase of the two plants under the Sena Sugar Co.
</P>
<P>
Ribeiro added that it needs to invest in rehabilitating the
road and railway linking the two plants with sea ports for
the exports of its sugar.
</P>
<P>
Mozambique produced 41,000 tons of sugar while its sugar
export once topped 350,000 in history. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
