<HEADLINE> Jordan to Send High-level Delegation to Doha </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
During a regular cabinet session today, it was decided that
the delegation would be led by Deputy Prime Minister for
Development and Prime Ministry Affairs Jawad Anani.
</P>
<P>
It will include Minister of Planning Rima Khalaf, Minister of
Trade, Industry and Supply Hani Moulki, Minister of Water and
Irrigation Munther Haddadin and other senior government officials
as well as businessmen from private sector, Jordan's official
news agency, Petra, reported.
</P>
<P>
Construction projects for the Red Sea port of Aqaba, water
transportation system, waste water treatment system as well as
other projects from the energy, industry, transport and tourism
sectors have been prepared to be presented at the Doha conference,
according to local media reports.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon, Syria, Saudi Arabia and the United Arab Emirates as
well as the Palestinian National Authority have threatened to
boycott the conference, which will be attended by Israel, in
protest against Israel's hard-line policy which caused the
deadlock in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Other Arab countries adopt a wait-and-see stance and condition
their attendance on improvement of Israel's policy.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian Foreign Minister Fayez Tarawneh said Monday that the
Doha gathering is not an Israeli conference and Israel will attend
it just like any other countries.
</P>
<P>
Jordan considers it an international forum which will
greatly benefit all the participants, especially those from the
private sector, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
Qatar has invited 92 countries and organizations to the
November 16 to 18 conference and expects some 2,500 foreign
participants.
</P>
<P>
The conference under the theme of creating a new partnership of
trade and economic development between the public and private
sectors beyond the year of 2000 is the fourth after those held in
Casablanca, Amman and Cairo. 
</P>
