<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ramos Approves Action Agenda on Currency Woes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel Ramos
today approved an action agenda to help the country recover from
the current financial crisis which is plaguing Southeast Asian
countries.
</P>
<P>
Ramos said the action agenda, prepared by the National Economic
and Development Authority (NEDA), will keep the country's
macro-economic fundamentals strong and sound.
</P>
<P>
Socio-Economic Planning Secretary and NEDA director General
Cielito Habito presented the agenda during a Legislative-Executive
Development Advisory Council meeting today.
</P>
<P>
Habito said the measures in the agenda aim to reduce the
current account deficit, maintain financial stability and the
growth momentum, keep prices stable, sustain the momentum of
reform, and support the disadvantaged.
</P>
<P>
Under the agenda, the national government is committed to
realizing a 7.6-billion-peso (223.5 million US dollar) surplus by
end-1997 despite higher interest payments.
</P>
<P>
The Department of Budget and Management and the NEDA shall
review the existing investment program to prioritize socially
efficient projects over those with low absorptive capacities or
cost-overruns.
</P>
<P>
Other measures include strengthening fiscal and monetary
coordination, monitoring government-owned and controlled firms,
rationalizing fiscal incentives packages, intensifying savings
campaigns and strengthening the banking system.  
</P>
</TEXT>
