<HEADLINE> Manila Begins Troop Withdrawal From Near Rebel Camp </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 21 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine military began to
pull back troops today from positions near a major Muslim rebels'
camp in the southern Philippines after the latter agreed to stop
executing people they themselves found guilty.
</P>
<P>
The compromise was reached during an emergency meeting between
negotiators from the government and the Moro Islamic Liberation
Front (MILF) in Cotabato city, capital of southern Maguindanao
province.
</P>
<P>
The MILF also agreed to reposition its fighters in three towns
in Maguindanao where they have been preparing for a possible
offensive by the military against their main headquarters in Camp
Abubakar.
</P>
<P>
Defense Secretary Fortunato Abat said the MILF vowed not to
initiate any more public executions before November 12 when the
MILF and the government begin their next round of peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Both parties will closely monitor the implementation of the
agreement to ease tension in the towns of Buldon, Matanog and
Barira, all surrounding Camp Abubakar, he added.
</P>
<P>
The government troops are now withdrawing from the three towns
and returning to positions they occupied before October 16, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Tension has been building around Camp Abubakar these days as
the military deployed as many as some 1,000 troops near the camp
in a sign of being poised for an attack on the rebel stronghold.
</P>
<P>
The troop movement was widely believed to be in retaliation for
a terrorist attack against a military camp last week and the
execution of "criminals" by the MILF early this month.
</P>
<P>
Last Tuesday, two Arabians raided a military camp in
Maguindanao, killing three soldiers before they themselves were
shot dead. The military blamed the attack on the MILF, but the
rebels strongly denied the charge.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, the MILF defied the country's constitution
and ordered the public execution of two people whom a rebel court
found guilty of murder. The executions were strongly condemned by
the government.  
</P>
</TEXT>
