<HEADLINE> South Asian Countries Meet Again on Free Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Representatives from the
seven South Asian countries met here today to formulate an action
plan for the transition to a South Asian Free Trade Area (SAFTA)
by the year 2001.
</P>
<P>
The second meeting of the Inter-Governmental Expert Group
(IGEG) on Transition to SAFTA will focus on finalizing its terms
of reference and draw a broader road map and timeframe for this
process, said a press release issued by the Kathmandu-based South
Asian Association for Regional Cooperation (SAARC) Secretariat.
</P>
<P>
Attending the three-day meeting are about 20 representatives
from Bangladesh, Bhutan, India, the Maldives, Nepal, Pakistan and
Sri Lanka -- all are SAARC member countries.
</P>
<P>
At a May summit held in the Maldives, the SAARC countries
decided to move from the South Asian Preferential Trading
Arrangement to the SAFTA by 2001.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting in late July in Kathmandu, the SAARC's
Inter-Governmental Group (IGG) on Trade Liberalization urged the
IGEG to expedite the formulation of an action plan on the SAFTA
which will serve as a blueprint for successive rounds of trade
negotiations by the IGG.
</P>
<P>
The first meeting of the IGEG was held in June 1997 in Thimphu,
the capital of Bhutan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
