<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Recommends MONUA Mandate Extension </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 21 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan today recommended extension of the mandate of the
United Nations Observer Mission in Angola (MONUA) for three months
until January 31, 1998.
</P>
<P>
In his report, the UN secretary-general expressed concern over
the very slow pace of the demilitarization of the National Union
for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) which was absolutely
essential for the successful implementation of the provisions of
the Lusaka Protocol, and the recent slowdown of the extension of
state administration into the areas controlled by the UNITA.
</P>
<P>
Annan called on the UNITA to finalize arrangements for the
transfer of all areas to government control and ensure that local
UNITA structures cooperate with the newly installed government
administrations.
</P>
<P>
The UN chief said that it would be difficult to consider that
the UNITA had taken all steps necessary to comply with the
provisions of Security Council resolutions unless additional
concrete steps were taken to accelerate the implementation of the
remaining tasks, including the transformation of Radio Vorgan into
a non-partisan broadcast facility.
</P>
<P>
He once again strongly urged the Angolan government and the
UNITA to take a number of specific steps that could enhance mutual
trust and confidence, and improve the prospects for national
reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
Annan also expressed concern over the reports of the presence
of Angolan armed elements in the Republic of the Congo and called
on all concerned to avoid any action that could exaggerate tension
in the conflict-torn country.
</P>
<P>
Annan stressed the continuing goodwill of the international
society was imperative to the peace process in Angola. He called
on the international society to make every effort to ensure that
gains achieved so far were sustained and reinforced. 
</P>
</TEXT>
