<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Firm Uses Fuel Cell to Turn Gas Into Electricity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, October 21 (xinhua) -- Plug Power, a New York-based
company, said today that it has successfully converted gasoline
into electricity through a fuel cell module with expectations for
lower energy costs and gas emission.
</P>
<P>
The company, which developed the technology in collaboration
with the U.S. Department of Energy, sees this as a breakthrough
and a major step toward the advancement of zero emission vehicles.
</P>
<P>
Unlike traditional combustion engines, fuel cells generate
electricity through an electro-chemical process, it said in a wire
service report.
</P>
<P>
The system converts the chemical energy of hydrogen -- and/or
hydrocarbons -- and oxygen into electrical energy and it produces
negligible amounts of sulfur and nitrogen oxides and less than
half the amount of carbon dioxide, a greenhouse gas, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
The company is considering mass manufacturing of this kind of
fuel cells and is planning to convert natural gas into electricity
for residential uses.
</P>
<P>
It believes that homeowners will save on their energy bills as
fuel cell operating costs will be lower than the cost of
electricity delivered through a utility's distribution system.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
