<HEADLINE> S. Leone Junta Places Order for War Planes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 21 (Xinhua) -- The military junta in Sierra
Leone has placed orders for three war planes to boost its attacks
on west African peacekeepers known as ECOMOG battling to overturn
the regime in the country.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria's defense spokesman, Col. Godwin Ugbo, said here today
that information on the buying of the jet fighters from Ukraine
was received from intelligence reports.
</P>
<P>
Unaware of whether the jet fighters had arrived, the spokesman
said "there is some connection between Sierra Leone and Ukraine."
</P>
<P>
He was referring to the alleged defying of the current
economic blockade on the junta by gun-running Ukrainian ships.
</P>
<P>
Ugbo urged the international community to call on Ukraine to
stop its subversive support to the illegal regime, saying that
giving support to the junta was against the convention of the
United Nations.
</P>
<P>
The buying of the fighter planes, according to military
sources, would help the junta to consolidate its war efforts
against ECOMOG, which has been raging for months after ECOMOG
stepped up attacks on the regime to restore ousted President
Ahmed Tejan Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
Kabbah was sacked by a military coup by Major Johnny Paul
Koroma on May 25 this year. The Koroma-led junta has vowed to
stay in power until 2001.
</P>
<P>
Nigerian Alpha jets are part of arsenals deployed to Sierra
Leone by ECOMOG to enforce an economic embargo imposed by the UN
and west African leaders.
</P>
<P>
However, the defense spokesman restated the difficulty of
sacking the junta through sanctions, saying that "economic
blockade is always difficult to succeed."  
</P>
</TEXT>
