<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French FM Intervenes in Dispute Over Vichy Period </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, October 21 (Xinhua) -- French Prime Minister Lionel
Jospin today intervened in the on-going debate over the trial of
former Vichy official Maurice Papon, and denied that the Socialist
Party is taking advantage of the trial to defame former President
Charles de Gaulle and the Gaullist movement he created.
</P>
<P>
In an article entitled "Assez! Assez! Assez! (Enough! Enough!
Enough!)" published today by Le Figaro, former parliament speaker
and president of the Gaullist Rally for the Republic (RPR)
Philippe Seguin said that the trial of Papon is "the pretext for
two trials:" those of General de Gaulle and Gaullist movement.
</P>
<P>
He accused the Socialist government of "benevolent complicity"
in the defamation movement which is aimed at replacing the classic
rightwing of France with the extreme-right National Front of
Jean-Marie Le Pen.
</P>
<P>
Just before Jospin was to make a statement over the trial of
Papon, Seguin quit the hemicycle meeting hall of the National
Assembly in an unprecedented confrontation with the prime minister
since the latter came to power in June.
</P>
<P>
"If there is a trial of Gaullism, it was not formulated by the
leaders of the majority or by the government," said Jospin.
</P>
<P>
As for the question of whether France was responsible for the
deportation of some 76,000 Jews to Nazi death camps during the
occupation period from 1940 to 1944, Jospin echoed a 1995
statement by President Jacques Chirac that it was the "French
state" which had done the "irreparable."
</P>
<P>
"France was in London or in Vercors, it was not in Vichy.
Vichy, it was the negation of France, of the republic," said
Jospin.
</P>
<P>
Vercors, a mountain area located in northern France, was the
shelter of many resistance fighters of France during World War II.
It was also the scene of a battle between French guerrillas and
German troops in June and July of 1944, in which many French
fighters were killed by the Germans.
</P>
<P>
Papon, 87, is being tried for the deportation of 1,690 Jews
from 1942 to 1944, when he served as the secretary general of
Gironde Prefecture under the Vichy regime.
</P>
<P>
Papon also served as Paris police chief in 1961 and budget
minister in 1978. 
</P>
</TEXT>
