<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Government Endorses EU Currency Plans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 21 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. government said
today that it expects a single European currency has no negative
impact on the U.S. economy or to the dollar's continued dominance
of the international financial system.
</P>
<P>
The Clinton administration endorsed preparations for a single
European currency although the U.S. government has no direct role
in preparations for the EMU.
</P>
<P>
"If the European Monetary Union works for Europe, it will work
for the United States," declared U.S. Deputy Treasury Secretary
Lawrence H. Summers.
</P>
<P>
"We have the same interest with regard to the creation of a
single economy.... We are well served when the region is vibrant
economically, and is working to open its markets and strengthen
its ties with the global economy," he told a penal of the U.S.
Senate.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. government in the past has been reluctant to comment
publicly on arrangements for the European Monetary Union, deeming
it inappropriate to meddle in debates over whether a single
currency is right for Europe or over details of how it should be
structured.
</P>
<P>
"When Europe is growing rapidly, it is a more dynamic market
for our exports, and a stronger partner for us around the world,"
Summers said.
</P>
<P>
Last year, America's trade with the EU's 15 nations exceeded
270 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Summers also said that it was difficult to predict with any
certainty what role the euro will have in the international
financial system. Currently 64 percent of foreign exchange
reserves worldwide are held in U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
