<HEADLINE> Bundesbank Chief Upbeat About Euro Filling Mark's Role </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, October 21 (Xinhua) -- German central bank president Hans
Tietmeyer expressed optimism today that a stable euro could fully
replace the mark as an international reserve and investment
currency.
</P>
<P>
"A stable euro can follow in the footsteps of the D-mark as a
worldwide investment and reserve currency and extend its role
considerably," he told a 50th anniversary meeting of the German
Association for the Protection of Shareholders in Duesseldorf.
</P>
<P>
Tietmeyer stressed the need for the same confidence in the euro
as in the mark, and assured that the German central bank, the
Bundesbank, would work very hard to prevent the inflationary
pressures which he warned would build up before the introduction
of the common European currency.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, he noted that any harm to the independence of the
future European Central Bank would "endanger the euro's
international reputation."
</P>
<P>
"The more convincingly the European Central bank can safeguard
price stability, the better the euro's chances," he added.
</P>
