<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 21 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Arab businessmen and investors called for the
creation of an Arab bank with a capital of 500 million U.S.
dollars to finance investments and trade in the Middle East, local
newspaper Beirut Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
The bank was essential to help boost investments in the Arab
states, the paper said, quoting recommendations at the end of the
three-day 7th Arab Business and Investors' Conference which
concluded here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The conference underlined the need for the establishment of big
Arab commercial banks to cope with the tough competition from
Western counterparts, according to the paper.
</P>
<P>
The participants urged Arab banks to merge to make them more
capable of handling a crisis, it reported.
</P>
<P>
The recommendations also called for modernizing and regulating
the banking system in Arab states to keep pace with developments.
</P>
<P>
The Arab states must remove all the obstacles to movements of
capital and to open their financial and banking markets to
increase the volume of transactions, the recommendations said.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt is striving to bring the annual volume of
foreign investment up to 3 billion U.S. dollars by the year of
2000 from the estimated 1.5 billion dollars for 1997, Chairman of
the General Authority for Investment Ibrahim Fawzi said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Industrial sectors had absorbed 70 percent of the foreign
investments in Egypt, according to Fawzi.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran's Central Bank Governor Mohsen Nourbakhsh
announced here today that it has paid off 75 percent of its
arrears.
</P>
<P>
Nourbakhsh was quoted by the official news agency IRNA as
saying that only 3.6 billion U.S. dollars has remained from
Iran's total rescheduled debts which should be paid next year.
</P>
<P>
Giving an explanation to the Parliament's session on the
economic situation of the country and the budget plan,
Nourbakhsh said that Iran's financial and credit status at
international level is satisfactory and foreign banks have
offered credit-lines to Iran.
</P>
<P>
Defining foreign debt is a problem in Iran. Estimates of
total liabilities ranged 30-35 billion dollars in the past few
years.
</P>
<P>
However, after two years of conflicting government statements
about Iran's real external debt position, Nourbakhsh stated in
January 1996 that the total external debts amounted to 23.41
billion dollars in September 1995.
</P>
<P>
The higher oil export revenue and tightened economic policy in
the past two years have reduced the pressure upon the debt
servicing of the Iranian government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
