<HEADLINE> Northern Iraqi Party Criticizes Turkish </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, October 21 (Xinhua) -- The Patriotic Union of
Kurdistan (PUK), a major northern Iraqi party, today accused
Turkey of taking a partial position over the northern Iraqi
issue.
</P>
<P>
Shazad Saib, the PUK representative in Ankara, rebuffed
Turkey's accusations that the PUK had provoked the latest
clashes with its rival, Kurdistan Democratic Party (KDP), the
Anatolia News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
"Turkey's involvement in the fight between us and the KDP has
actually ended the Ankara process," Saib said.
</P>
<P>
Turkish military jets repeatedly bombed the PUK positions in
northern Iraq on the grounds of striking the rebels of Turkey's
outlawed group the Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK) fleeing into the
area controlled by the PUK, which maintains a relaxed
relationship with the PKK.
</P>
<P>
Twelves PUK militants and eight civilians were reportedly
killed in the Turkish air raids.
</P>
<P>
The pro-Iranian PUK and the KDP, allegedly backed by Turkey
and Iraq, have been fighting each other for the control of
northern Iraq following the 1991 Gulf War. Their clashes
intensified since early last week.
</P>
<P>
Turkey, Britain and the United States, three sponsors of the
Ankara process, had blamed the PUK for the fresh clashes,
demanding immediate withdrawal of the PUK troops from certain
areas.
</P>
<P>
The Ankara process, designed to restore peace and stability in
northern Iraq, has witnessed three rounds of peace talks in the
Turkish capital since last year.
</P>
<P>
"I am not sure if this is a process for war or for peace,"
Saib added.
</P>
<P>
The PUK denied the three sponsors' charges that it provoked
the latest clashes with the KDP, saying that they had stopped
offensive even before the start of a cease-fire reached last
Friday.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, the two warring northern Iraqi parties and
representatives from Turkey, Britain and the United States held
a meeting here to discuss the current situation in northern
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, the PUK was again urged to withdraw its
forces from the positions captured over the last several
days. 
</P>
</TEXT>
