<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Money Supply Growth Slows Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Germany's money supply growth
slowed down in September and was for the fourth successive month
kept within the official targets for the year, the Bundesbank
reported today in Frankfurt.
</P>
<P>
The M3 supply last month was 5.2 percent above the average for
the last quarter of 1996, compared with 5.8 percent in August and
5.7 percent in July, said the German central bank.
</P>
<P>
It attributed the lower growth rate in September to a slight
drop in cash in circulation and in bank lending to private
customers and companies.
</P>
<P>
The M3 consists of cash in circulation, sight deposits, fixed
deposits under four years and savings deposits with a mandatory
withdrawal period. It was a key factor in deciding interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The Bundesbank has set a target corridor of 3.5 to 6.5 percent
this year for the M3 growth.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
