<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study Shows Gas Emissions up Sharply in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Cars, power plants and
factories in the U.S. released record amounts of the pollutants
believed to contribute to global warming, according to a U.S.
governmental study released Monday.
</P>
<P>
A report of the U.S. Department of Energy carried by newspapers
today indicated that U.S. emissions of the so-called greenhouse
gases rose 3.4 percent from 1995 to 1996. Much of the increase was
attributed to an increase in carbon dioxide emissions, which come
from burning fossil fuels.
</P>
<P>
Cold weather and higher natural gas prices meant more reliance
on coal, which emits more carbon dioxide. Another factor was the
vigorous economy, which kept factories and power plants operating
at higher capacities, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The increase, the largest in recent times, illustrates how
difficult it will be for U.S. businesses and consumers to reduce
greenhouse gas levels.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. government will propose mandatory limits on developed
countries' carbon dioxide output. But the plan is expected to be
much weaker than the demands of environmentalists, who call global
warming the Earth's No.1 problem. A European plan would lower
those emissions to 2.8 billion tons a year by 2010. If no action
is taken, emissions are likely to be about 4.1 billion tons a year
by then, according to the newspaper reports.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. plan is expected to propose smaller cuts over a longer
period, perhaps a return to the 1990 level of 3.3 billion tons a
year by 2020 or 2030.
</P>
<P>
In December, officials from 169 countries will meet in Japan to
finalize the treaty now being worked out in Bonn, Germany.
</P>
<P>
Since the mid-1980s, the Earth's average temperature has risen
one-half to one degree Fahrenheit, which scientists attribute
partially to heat trapped by greenhouse gases. It is feared that
continued warming could bring more floods and droughts and sea
levels high.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
