<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-21 20:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Issues Statement on Greek Air Force </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, October 21 (Xinhua) -- The Cypriot government said
today that it reserves the right to decide whether it should avoid
inviting the Greek Air Force to participate in its military
exercises.
</P>
<P>
This position was outlined in a Foreign Ministry statement
issued here today in response to statements made by U.S. State
Department spokesman James Rubin.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference Monday, Rubin called for a
return to an overflight ban over Cyprus. "We would hope that all
sides would appreciate the benefits of reinstituting a complete
and open-ended moratorium on military overflights in Cyprus at
the earliest possible time," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot Foreign Ministry statement, however, explains that
"there has never been an agreement for a moratorium of
overflights in Cyprus' sovereign airspace."
</P>
<P>
Cyprus held a military exercise code-named "Nikiforos '97"
on October 10-14, with the participation of Greek air and naval
forces.
</P>
<P>
The statement clarifies that the Cypriot government announced
last year that in an effort to contribute to a good climate to
conduct the U.N.-sponsored direct negotiations, it had decided not
to ask the participation of the Greek Air Force in exercises until
September this year.
</P>
<P>
But "the results of the talks in New York and Montreux
(Switzerland) did not justify an extension of the unilateral
decision" during the five-day military exercises, which ended last
week, the statement says.
</P>
<P>
"Parallel with our unilateral decision, the U.S. administration
said that Turkey decided to avoid overflights for the same
period," it says.
</P>
<P>
"We would like to remind that Turkey repeatedly violated
its promise toward the U.S. administration," the statement notes.
</P>
<P>
It says that the Cypriot government reserves the right to
decide, if it judges that circumstances require so, whether it
should or not and for how long, avoid extending invitations to the
Greek Air Force to participate in its military exercises.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops and took over the northern third of the island in the wake
of a failed coup by Greek Cypriots seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus problem has remained unsolved despite the U.N. and
international community's peace efforts for the past 23
years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
