<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> People's Daily Issues Commentary on Interest Rate Cut  (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 22 (Xinhua) -- The People's Daily, the leading
newspaper of China, will publish a commentary tomorrow
reinterating the need to follow a moderately tight monetary policy
and conduct proper economic macro-control.
</P>
<P>
The commentary, titled Adhere to an Appropriately Tight
Monetary Policy and Exercise Proper Economic Macro-Control,
describes the decision of the People's Bank of China to lower the
interest rates on bank loans and deposits as of tomorrow as a new
important move by the central bank to apply the lever of interest
rates, follow a moderately tight monetary policy and conduct
proper and timely economic macro-control.
</P>
<P>
"To readjust the interest rates on loans and deposits is
imperative to exercise economic macro-control," the commentary
says.
</P>
<P>
The timely interest readjustments since economic macro-control
started in 1993, including two raises and two cuts, have
effectively helped to curb the growth of money supply and boost
the sustained, rapid and sound development of the national
economy, it notes.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the effective implementation of macro-control
policies, the national economy has continued to grow steadily and
healthily while prices have been on a steady downward trend, the
commentary says.
</P>
<P>
Between January and September this year, the retail price index
and the consumer price index rose 1.3 and 3.4 percent respectively
from the same period of last year. The two indices by the year-end
are expected to be around two and less than four percent.
</P>
<P>
Calculated on this basis, the actual annual interest rate on
one-year deposits is 6.17 and 4.07 percent respectively after
inflation is adjusted.
</P>
<P>
This level of positive interest rate is the highest in China
since 1990 and is about two percentage points higher than the
interest level in many developed countries, the commentary says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971022.0064 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> People's Daily Issues Commentary on Interest Rate Cut  (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The decision of the People's Bank of China to further lower the
interest rates is in response to declining prices, and is to
reduce the interest cost of enterprises and promote the sustained,
rapid and healthy development of the national economy, the
commentary points out.
</P>
<P>
It adds that the decision is made under the principle of
protecting the interests of the depositors, adding that the actual
interest rates and interest income of depositors will increase
after the latest readjustment.
</P>
<P>
Though the interest rate cut is aimed to reduce the interest
cost of enterprises, it must be pointed out that the current
difficulties of Chinese enterprises are not a result of high
interest rates, the commentary says.
</P>
<P>
It will not work to resolve the difficulties of enterprises
merely through lowering the interest level, the commentary notes,
adding that the key to revitalizing the state-owned enterprises is
to do what set forth by Party leader Jiang Zemin in his report to
the 15th national congress of the Communist Party of China last
month.
</P>
<P>
The commentary points out that the decision to lower the
interest rates, made under the backdrop of dropping prices, must
not be interpreted as a sign to ease the supply of bank credits
and change the moderately tight monetary policy.
</P>
<P>
The latest interest rate cut is also conducive to narrowing the
gap in the interest rate level of the Chinese yuan and major
foreign currencies, thereby preventing speculators from taking
advantages of the differentiations, the commentary says. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
