<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Four CIS Nations Decide to Set Up Free Trade Zone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Russia, Belarus, Kazakhstan and
Kyrgyzstan decided, at a meeting here today of the parliamentary
committee of the four countries, to set up a free-trade zone.
</P>
<P>
Among the 12 resolutions passed at the meeting was the one
providing that value-added tax (VAT) should be levied at the place
of destination of goods rather than the place of production.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, said an Itar-Tass news agency report, also elected
Kazakh President Nursultan Nazarbayev chairman of the so-called
"Union of Four" to replace Belarus President Alexander Lukashenko.
</P>
<P>
After the gathering, Nazarbayev said "different rates of
integration" among some members of the Commonwealth of Independent
States (CIS) will set a good example to other CIS countries.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that it is of extreme importance for the four
nations "to create a real common market and free space."
</P>
<P>
Russian President Boris Yeltsin told reporters that the
Russia-Belarus Union and the "Union of Four" are keeping the CIS
together, and are the force behind solutions to many problems.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin noted that "a very bold resolution" was adopted, also
at the meeting today, on the customs union and the customs duty.
</P>
<P>
Kyragyz President Askar Akayev said he was satisfied with the
current integration pace as conditions have been turning favorable
for the process since the "Union of Four" was forged 18 months ago.
</P>
<P>
On March 29, 1996, Russia, Belarus, Kazakhstan and Kyrgyzstan
signed an agreement on deepening their integration in economic and
social areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
