<HEADLINE> HK Reaches Agreement with Germany, Britain to Avoid Double Taxation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong has reached
agreements separately with Germany and Britain on arrangements to
provide double taxation relief for airline income.
</P>
<P>
A Hong Kong government spokesman said here today that the
amendments have been made to the Air Services Agreement between
the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) and Germany to
incorporate the relief arrangements.
</P>
<P>
"As for the relief arrangements with the United Kingdom, they
are included in the Air Services Agreement with the United Kingdom
which was signed on July 25," he said.
</P>
<P>
Under the arrangements, Hong Kong will tax the income generated
from international traffic of Hong Kong airlines derived from
Germany and Britain and which has been granted full tax relief by
the two countries respectively.
</P>
<P>
In return, Hong Kong will forgo the right to tax the income of
German and British airlines derived from Hong Kong if such income
is subject to tax in their respective countries.
</P>
<P>
"It is our policy to include provisions on double taxation
relief for airline income into Air Services Agreements negotiated
between Hong Kong and our bilateral aviation partners on a case by
 case basis," the spokesman explained.  
</P>
</TEXT>
