<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1530 GMT, October 22 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu sparked
another political storm today when his secret inciting remarks
against the leftists were recorded and broadcast on TV and radio
stations.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting Tuesday with popular Rabbi Yitzhak Kadouri,
Netanyahu accused the leftists of forgetting that they are Jews by
entrusting the security of the country to Arabs.
</P>
<P>
"The left has forgotten what it is to be Jews. They think
they'll place the defense of the land in the hands of the Arabs.
That the Arabs will look after us. Have you ever heard such a
thing", Netanyahu reportedly told Kadouri.
</P>
<P>
His remarks were recorded by an Israeli radio reporter without
his knowledge and broadcast as the leading story on television and
radio stations Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Israel Radio today, Netanyahu defended
his remarks saying that they "were taken out of the context." He
said he only doubted how Kosher (purity of being a Jew) the
leftists are as Jews since they entrusted Israeli security to
Arabs.
</P>
<P>
PHNOM PENH -- Cambodia'a Second Prime Minister Hun Sen today
said the deposed co-premier Prince Norodom Ranariddh would not be
allowed to run in elections in May even if he is convicted and
then pardoned from criminal charges.
</P>
<P>
In a meeting with Japanese Ambassador to Cambodia Masaki Saito,
Hun Sen rejected Tokyo's proposal that a draft electoral law be
amended to allow convicted criminals to stand for election if they
receive a royal pardon, a senior aide to Hun Sen said.
</P>
<P>
"Hun Sen said to do that would allow others who have received
amnesty to also run for election, for example (former Khmer Rouge
leader) Ieng Sary and common criminals," Prak Sokhon told
reporters after the meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
