<HEADLINE> Philippine Towns on Alert for Terrorist Attacks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 22 (Xinhua) -- At least three towns in Basilan
province, the southern Philippines, have been put on "red alert"
for possible terrorist attacks by an extremist Muslim rebel group,
the Philippine News Agency said today.
</P>
<P>
Security has been tightened in Isabela city, capital of
Basilan, and the towns of Lamitan and Tipo-Tipo following reports
of an impending attack by the extremist Abu Sayyaf, the agency
said.
</P>
<P>
Local officials said they had received reliable information
that Abu Sayyaf planned to spread terror in the provincial capital
and other towns.
</P>
<P>
Abu Sayyaf, which has been pursued hard by the military for
kidnapping 10 people on October 15 along a highway in Basilan,
have stepped up attacks in the island province these days.
</P>
<P>
Military reports said earlier that nine of the 10 kidnapped
victims had been summarily executed by the extremists and that the
remaining capturer, a woman, is still listed as missing.
</P>
<P>
During the past few days, Abu Sayyaf launched a new wave of
attacks in Basilan, killing 10 people and wounding scores of
others.
</P>
<P>
Abu Sayyaf and the Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) are the
two remaining Muslim rebel groups still fighting the government.
</P>
<P>
The mainstream Moro National Liberation Front (MNLF) signed a
peace agreement with Manila last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971022.0078 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Silting Not Expected to Impede Yangtze Dam Project: Expert </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YICHANG, October 22 (Xinhua) -- An expert working in Yichang
said that silting in the water diversion channel no longer poses a
problem for the project to dam the Yangtze River, an event marking
completion of the first phase of the giant Three Gorges Project.
</P>
<P>
The water diversion channel between two cofferdams, which will
be closed on November 8, currently facilitates 53.9 percent of
water flowing through the dam site and is expected to be handling
over 70 percent of the flow prior to the aforementioned date. The
increased capacity will meet the requirements for water diversion
when damming the river, according Wang Jiazhu, the director of
technology.
</P>
<P>
Wang works as deputy general manager of technology for the
China Yangtze Three Gorges Project Development. Corp., which is
undertaking the country's largest water control project in history.
</P>
<P>
Wang said that silting in the channel will create difficulties
for the damming effort by forcing more water towards the
cofferdams in the main channel.
</P>
<P>
The channel, which stretches some 3.5 km in length and is 350 m
wide and 20 m deep, will be the only Yangtze River channel through
the dam area for the next six years.
</P>
<P>
The channel, which opened in May last year, was subject to
heavy silting during the flood season from June-September owing to
the heavy volume of silt, and the fact that most of the water
flowed through the cofferdams and spilled into the main channel.
</P>
<P>
"Silting, a normal phenomenon in such cases, will not affect
normal navigation, and will not create environmental problems,"
said Wang.
</P>
<P>
Narrowing the openings of the cofferdams will enable more water
to flow through the channel, with the flow rate of 1.3-1.4 meters
per second expected to wash away silt.
</P>
<P>
Wang said silting in the water diversion channel is being
monitored closely, and an alternate plan is being drafted in
case silting creates a problem in blocking the river.
</P>
<P>
The width of a cofferdam upstream has been reduced to 150
meters and will be further reduced to 130 meters in two days.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971022.0079 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-22 14:37 </DATE_TIME>
