<HEADLINE> France Plays Down Report on Algeria Chemical Weapons Tests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, October 22 (Xinhua) -- France today played down a media
report claiming France had been committing secret tests on
chemical weapons in Algeria until 16 years after its independence.
</P>
<P>
"We have never denied these facts nor confirmed that such
activities did take place," said French Foreign Ministry spokesman
Yves Doutriaux, about the Nouvel Observateur magazine report.
</P>
<P>
These tests, Doutriaux said, "were very officially recognized
in the voluntary declarations made by France at the Organization
for Interdiction of Chemical Weapons."
</P>
<P>
Nouvel Observateur, a French magazine, said in its latest issue
that a secret French base for testing chemical arms was
established in 1935 in the Sahara desert in Algeria.
</P>
<P>
France had been kept using the base, codenamed "B2-Namous,"
until 16 years after Algeria's independence in 1962, it said.
</P>
</TEXT>
