<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Falls as Concerns on Asia Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 22 (Xinhua) --The Australian dollar plummeted
to its lowest level in two and a half years today, driven down by
fears the Asian currency crisis will have a negative impact on the
local economy.
</P>
<P>
The local unit closed at 71.22 US cents, more than
one-and-a-half US cents lower from 72.84 US cents late yesterday.
</P>
<P>
Global investment bank Goldman Sachs sparked heavy selling of
the Australian dollar when it published a report warning clients
of the likely negative impact of the Asian currency and economic
crisis on the Australian arena.
</P>
<P>
In its latest Weekly Analyst publication, Goldman Sachs said
recent developments in Southeast Asia were likely to be a "major
economic shock" for Australia and New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
Against the Japanese yen, the Australian dollar was at 85.51
from 88.06 and against the Deutsche mark it was at 1.2739, from
1.2927. 
</P>
