<HEADLINE> EU, World Bank Hold Donors Conference for Albania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, October 22 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission and
the World Bank today held a donors conference to discuss Albania's
economic and financial recovery.
</P>
<P>
Participating in the conference were 26 countries, including
Albania, and 13 international institutions.
</P>
<P>
The conference, a follow-up to the ministerial conference held
in Rome on October 17, was expected to raise around 100 million
U.S. dollars to increase the momentum of international support for
the political and economic stabilization of Albania.
</P>
<P>
The 15-nation European Union (EU) has pledged 250,000 dollars
toward the donation.
</P>
<P>
Participants were also expected to donate another 79 million
dollars in support of institution building, macro-economic
stabilization, structural reform, economic recovery and poverty
alleviation in the Balkan country.
</P>
<P>
Participants of the donors conference noted that situation in
Albania is normalizing and the prerequisites for donor assistance
had been substantially met.
</P>
<P>
But they added that security conditions still need to improve
so as to enable investments and projects to be fully and
effectively implemented.
</P>
<P>
Albanian Prime Minister Fatos Nano reaffirmed the participants
of the conference that his country will strive for macro-economic
stability to take hold and for his country to get back on track of
economic development. 
</P>
