<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 22 (Xinhua) -- The Australian share market
finished on a high note, buoyed by steady trade and added
confidence following the release of September quarter inflation
data today.
</P>
<P>
"I think it gave the market confidence, and things have settled
down," Michael Coombes from Macquarie Equities said.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index finished at 2,682.9, up 32.2 points.
</P>
<P>
Australia's annual inflation rate slumped to a 35-year low,
Australian Bureau of Statistics figures showed. The consumer price
index fell 0.4 percent in the September quarter, driven down by
lower mortgage rates and medical costs.
</P>
<P>
Federal Treasury's underlying inflation rate rose 0.3 percent
in the September quarter, for an annual rate of 1.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index gained 69.7 points to 4,444.5 and the
all resources index edged up 0.9 points to 1,293.2.
</P>
<P>
Amongst the leading industrial stocks, Brambles jumped 1.05
Australian dollars to 27.90 Australian dollars, Australian Gas
Light added 27 cents to 9.77 Australian dollars and Lend Lease
leapt 2.72 Australian dollars to 33.32 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The banks all finished up with the exception of ANZ, which slid
23.5 cents to 10.85 Australian dollars on turnover of 7.9 million
shares, while the National Australia Bank added 40.2 cents to
21.37 Australian dollars, Westpac gained 11.6 cents to 8.816
Australian dollars and the Commonwealth Bank rose 25 cents to
16.85 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Rupert Murdoch's News Corp jumped 22.8 cents to 6.958
Australian dollars while its preferred shares rose 13 cents to
6.20 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Amongst the mining stocks, bellwether BHP dropped 17 cents to
14.88 Australian dollars while global miner Rio Tinto closed up
22.6 cents at 20.22 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Woodside Petroleum gained 28 cents to 12.75 Australian dollars
while Oil Search Ltd lost 13 cents to 3.17 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gold index was down 1.8 points at 1,289.0 with gold leader
Normandy dropping two cents to 1.78 Australian dollars and
Plutonic Resources falling five cents to 3.20 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 339.54 million shares worth 1.016 billion
Australian dollars (731.52 million US dollars) with rises
outnumbering falls 614 to 530.  
</P>
