<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tung Chee Hwa Confident About Hong Kong's Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 22 (Xinhua) -- "We are moving forward in Hong
Kong with pride and confidence," Tung Chee Hwa, chief executive of
China's Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) of China,
told Britons here today.
</P>
<P>
In a keynote address to British business leaders and political
figures at the Royal Institute of International Affairs, Tung said
he was very confident about Hong Kong's future because the HKSAR
enjoys "a high degree of autonomy under the 'one country, two
systems' concept as guaranteed by the Joint Declaration and the
Basic Law."
</P>
<P>
"Four months after the establishment of the HKSAR, there is not
a single suggestion that autonomy has been violated," said the
chief executive who arrived here Tuesday for a three-day visit.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time for Tung to visit Britain in the
capacity of Hong Kong's chief executive since the region's return
to China on July 1 after 156 years of British colonial rule. He
said his mission was to give friends overseas some first-hand
information about Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Tung said the reality is that business continues as it has done
before. "The economy is growing at a healthy rate, with the gross
domestic product (GDP) forecast for 1997 at 5.4 percent."
</P>
<P>
"The Hong Kong dollar, backed by our huge foreign reserve and
our sound economic and financial fundamentals, maintains its
strength amidst the turmoil on Asian currencies. Hong Kong
people's confidence towards the HKSAR Administration and the
future is running high," he said.
</P>
<P>
Since July 1, He said, Hong Kong people have been exercising
the rights of free speech, of demonstration, and of scrutinizing
government policies and decisions.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of the "one country, two systems" concept developed by
China, Tung expressed the belief that its successful
implementation in Hong Kong can serve as "a significant step
towards the greater and final objective of reunification of the
entire nation."
</P>
<P>
As part of China, Tung said, "Hong Kong can not and should not
do things which are not in the long-term interests of China."
"Certainly Hong Kong should not be permitted to be used as a base
to destabilize China," he added.
</P>
<P>
"China needs social stability, China also needs stability and
peace in Asia and around the world," Tung stressed.
</P>
<P>
He also voiced his confidence that China will be more open and
more prosperous as it enters the 21st century, while Hong Kong
will be one of the chief beneficiaries of China's growth and
prosperity.
</P>
<P>
Tung's trip is aimed at strengthening the close economic and
trade ties between Hong Kong and Britain, sources said.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong is Britain's second largest export market in the
Asia-Pacific region while Britain is the leading foreign investor
in Hong Kong with investment in its manufacturing and services
sectors estimated at around 20 billion U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
