<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Revises Internet Guidelines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, October 22 (Xinhua) -- The Singapore Broadcasting
Authority (SBA) announced today that it has revised its Internet
Code of Practice, and for the first time, it has issued Industry
Guidelines for users and content providers.
</P>
<P>
With the revision, there are clearer provisions which spell out
the obligations of service and content providers, and define what
is prohibited.
</P>
<P>
Under the changes, there are more precise terms on "prohibited
materials," which, according to the new Code of Practice, refer to
"material that is objectionable on the grounds of public interest,
public morality, public order, public security, national harmony,
or is otherwise prohibited by applicable Singapore laws."
</P>
<P>
The new code also clarifies obligations of providers for
services like news groups, private discussions and public bulletin
boards.
</P>
<P>
The new code excludes previous clauses on issues like
"disaffection against the Government" and promotion of "religious
deviations or occult practices." SBA says these are covered under
other existing legislation.
</P>
<P>
The new Code of Practice will take effect on November 1, this
year, the SBA said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
