<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-22 13:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>   Netanyahu's Remarks Against Oppositions Sparks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu sparked another political storm today when his
secret inciting remarks against the leftists were recorded and
broadcast on TV and radio stations.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting Tuesday with popular Rabbi Yitzhak Kadouri,
Netanyahu accused the leftists of forgetting that they are Jews
by entrusting the security of the country to Arabs.
</P>
<P>
"The left has forgotten what it is to be Jews. They think
they'll place the defense of the land in the hands of the
Arabs. That the Arabs will look after us. Have you ever heard
such a thing", Netanyahu reportedly told Kadouri.
</P>
<P>
His remarks were recorded by an Israeli radio reporter without
his knowledge and broadcast as the leading story on television
and radio stations Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Israel Radio today, Netanyahu defended
his remarks saying that they "were taken out of the context." He
said he only doubted how Kosher (purity of being a Jew) the
leftists are as Jews since they entrusted Israeli security to
Arabs.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu's remarks set off another political storm as the
upset oppositions have began a new campaign to oust him from the
office. Netanyahu has yet cleared himself of the recent
political crisis sparked by the failed attempt to assassinate a
Hamas leader in Jordanian capital Amman in late September.
</P>
<P>
Leading opposition party Labor's leader Ehud Barak blasted
Netanyahu for inciting against the left by making "whispering
sedition into the ear of such an important and venerable Rabbi on
a holiday of unity." He said Netanyahu does not have right to
teach the left what Judaism is or what responsibility for
security is.
</P>
<P>
The Labor's caucus in the Knesset (Parliament) called
Netanyahu's remarks as an extra strategy to divide the Jewish
nation. And Labor lawmaker Ohpir Pines has filed a police
complaint against the prime minister for incitement.
</P>
<P>
Pines said that given the remarks made Tuesday, Netanyahu is
clearly responsible for the incitement that led to the
assassination of former Labor Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin, who
was shot on November 4, 1995 by a radical Jew who accused Rabin
of being a traitor by giving land to Arabs.
</P>
<P>
He demanded for a review of Netanyahu's role in Rabin's
murder. Following Rabin's assassination, Netanyahu was blamed for
organizing rightist demonstrations and propaganda against Rabin's
government, in which he often made harsh attacks against Rabin
and his peace policies.
</P>
<P>
The caucus head of another opposition party Meretz, Haim
Merom, said his party would table a non-confidence motion
against the prime minister during the opening session of the
Knesset's winter session next Monday.
</P>
<P>
Barak has been meeting secretly with political leaders of
coalition parties and even key figures within the Netanyahu-led
ruling Likud party in a bid to win the support of 80 lawmakers
needed to oust the prime minister without holding new election
of the Knesset. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
