<DOCNO> XIE19971022.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Economic Growth Decelerating Since April </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Japan's economy has been slowing
down since April, following the consumption tax hike from 3 to 5
percent, Bank of Japan (BOJ) Governor Yasuo Matsushita said today.
</P>
<P>
"It is difficult to judge whether the nation's economy has
returned, after the summer, to the recovery path that was seen
before the deceleration," Matsushita told a press conference.
</P>
<P>
Matsushita's remarks reflected some bearish reports on regional
economies at a quarterly meeting of BOJ branch managers, held
Monday and Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Many branch managers reported stagnation in personal
consumption and housing investment as a result of the consumption
tax hike, and expressed their worries on further negative effects,
Matsushita said.
</P>
<P>
"Business confidence among corporate executives has been
affected by these negative factors, according to the managers, and
some of them said their regional economies have actually come to a
standstill," the central bank chief said.
</P>
<P>
Under these circumstances, the central bank "will continue
giving policy priorities to consolidating the basis for economic
recovery," Matsushita said, hinting that there would be no
immediate change in Japan's current easy monetary policy.
</P>
<P>
The BOJ has maintained an easy monetary policy for more than
two years, with its official discount rate at a historic low of
0.5 percent per annum.
</P>
<P>
Despite the economic deceleration, Matsushita reiterated that
"the basis for economic recovery has not been damaged, and is
underpinned by favorable net exports and corporate capital
investment."
</P>
<P>
Citing an improving employment index and employees income as
positive factors, Matsushita expressed his belief that the economy
will eventually come back to a mild recovery path. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
