global warming, the Clinton Administration has devised a set of
rewards for companies that cut emissions of heat-trapping gases
faster than the Government would require under a pending
international treaty.
</P>
<P>
-- The Clinton Administration reversed itself Tuesday and said
it would support legislation to overhaul the Internal Revenue
Service by creating an outside board with broad authority over the
tax-collection agency and strengthening the rights of taxpayers
who think they are being treated unfairly.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post:
</P>
<P>
-- A rigorous new test of what American students know in
science has revealed that many of them are not demonstrating even
basic competence in the subject in certain grades.
</P>
<P>
-- The White House has reversed strategy on the free-trade
proposal, and has turned its focus to the Senate.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal:
</P>
<P>
-- The Energy Department hailed as a breakthrough a new
electric-car design that uses a fuel cell instead of bulky
batteries, and turns ordinary gasoline into hydrogen source.
Arthur D. Little researchers are working to develop the system
into one that would cut emission 95 percent and get 80 mpg.
</P>
<P>
USA Today:
</P>
<P>
-- Justice Department officials on Tuesday defended the
selection of a scientist with no forensic experience to head the
FBI's troubled crime laboratory.
</P>
<P>
-- New photos from Nasa's Hubble Space Telescope released
Tuesday give the first close-up look at one of nature's most
violent events, the collision of galaxies. 
