<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Spokesman Denies ABC Report on Sale of Organs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 22 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese Foreign Ministry
spokesman today denied a US television report that some hospitals
under the Chinese People's Liberation Army (PLA) sell foreigners
the organs of convicts sentenced to death.
</P>
<P>
When asked to confirm the report carried by an ABC documentary,
Spokesman Shen Guofang said the report was piecemeal and nothing
more than a "pure fabrication."
</P>
<P>
Shen said that relevant Chinese departments have conducted
investigations and confirmed the falsity of the report.
</P>
<P>
All scenes in the documentary, with the exception of a few
showing entrances to medical centers in South China which are open
to foreigners, are "fabricated" and have nothing to do with PLA
hospitals, said Shen.
</P>
<P>
"Military surgeons" appearing in the documentary are not PLA
medical personnel, he added.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Ministry of Public Health, Ministry of Foreign
Trade and Economic Cooperation, and the General Administration of
Customs have issued regulations banning sales of human tissues and
organs, and banning donations or exchanges of human tissues and
organs with foreign institutions or individuals, said Shen.
</P>
<P>
Voluntary organ transplants in a few Chinese hospitals with
advanced technology are carried out in strict conformity with the
relevant state rules and regulations, according to Shen. He said
that hospitals have never sold the organs of convicts sentenced to
death. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
