<HEADLINE> HK Land Registry Trading Fund Makes Big Profit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 22 (Xinhua) -- The Land Registry Trading
Fund of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) had a
very successful operation in 1996-1997, with a net profit of 131.4
million HK dollars (about 16.89 million U.S. dollars), local
officials said today.
</P>
<P>
The figure represents an annual rate of return of 29.1 percent
on average net fixed assets and 19.1 percentage points higher than
the target of 10 percent, Secretary for Planning, Environment and
Lands of the SAR government Bowen Leung said when presenting the
Fourth Annual Report of the fund to the Provisional Legislative
Council.
</P>
<P>
"This significant outturn reflects an increase in workload and
an effective and rigorous control over operating expenses," chief
of the Land Registry and General Manager of the fund Anthony
Cooper told the legislators. "This has enabled the Land Registry
to continue investing in large-scale information technology
projects to bring about improved services at reduced costs."
</P>
<P>
The Land Registry is one of the first trading fund government
departments, established in August 1993 to operate on a
self-financing basis. Its primary objective is to deliver
value-for-money and business-friendly service to customers.
</P>
</TEXT>
