<HEADLINE> Hun Sen Says Ranariddh Not Allowed to Run for Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Cambodia'a Second Prime
Minister Hun Sen today said the deposed co-premier Prince Norodom
Ranariddh would not be allowed to run in elections in May even if
he is convicted and then pardoned from criminal charges.
</P>
<P>
In a meeting with Japanese Ambassador to Cambodia Masaki Saito,
Hun Sen rejected Tokyo's proposal that a draft electoral law be
amended to allow convicted criminals to stand for election if they
receive a royal pardon, a senior aide to Hun Sen said.
</P>
<P>
"Hun Sen said to do that would allow others who have received
amnesty to also run for election, for example (former Khmer Rouge
leader) Ieng Sary and common criminals," Prak Sokhon told
reporters after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
A Phnom Penh court has charged the prince, who was ousted in
early July, with illegally importing weapons and negotiating with
the outlawed Khmer Rouge guerrilla faction.
</P>
<P>
The international community has demanded that Hun Sen allow
Ranariddh to run for general elections scheduled for May.
</P>
<P>
During today's meeting, Hun Sen also pledged to accept results
of the elections and said he welcomed international observers to
monitor the polls, Prak Sokhon said.
</P>
<P>
Japan, Cambodia's largest aid donor, is expected to raise the
issue of the prince's participation in the elections again next
month when Hun Sen visits Tokyo from November 5 to 10.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen is expected to meet with Japanese Prime Minister
Ryutaro Hashimoto during the visit, according to Prak Sokhon.
</P>
</TEXT>
