<HEADLINE> Mandela Will Not Mediate Lockerbie Issue: FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 22 (Xinhua) -- President Nelson Mandela
will not mediate between Libya and the U.S. over the hand-over of
two Libyans allegedly involved in the Lockerbie air disaster,
local media quoted Foreign Minister Alfred Nzo as saying tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Nzo made the clarification after Egyptian media reported that
Mandela would try to convince Libyan leader Col Muammar Qaddafi
to reach an understanding with the west over the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Ministry spokesman Piet Swanepoel said reports that
Mandela intended to mediate on Lockerbie issue were simply
speculation.
</P>
<P>
"There has never been any intention on the part of South
Africa to assume the role of mediator on this issue," he said.
</P>
<P>
Swanepoel said Mandela may discuss the matter with the Libyan
leader during their meeting, but it was not on the official
agenda.
</P>
<P>
Mandela is expected to arrive in Libya today for a
controversial state visit, which was opposed by the United States
and South African opposition parties.
</P>
<P>
Mandela will travel to Tripoli by road to sidestep a U.N.
flight embargo against Libya, imposed after Libya refused to
extradite the two suspects in the 1988 bombing of a Pan Am
jetliner over Lockerbie, Scotland.
</P>
<P>
Libya, backed by the Organization of African Unity and the
Non-aligned Movement, has suggested a compromise that the trial
of the two Libyans be held in a neutral country, by Scottish
judges under Scottish law. But the proposal was rejected by the
UN and the US. 
</P>
</TEXT>
