<HEADLINE> China to Increase Trade with Finland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Minister of Foreign
Trade and Economic Co-operation Wu Yi, meeting here today with the
Finnish Minister of European Affairs Ole Norrback, said that China
is confident of economic co-operation and trade prospects with
Finland, and that there is great potential for development.
</P>
<P>
China needs Finland's advanced technology, managerial
expertise, capital, and markets, Wu said, adding that Finland also
needs China's markets and commodities.
</P>
<P>
After the 15th National Party Congress, China will be more open,
offering more opportunities for Finnish products to enter Chinese
market, she said.
</P>
<P>
Stronger co-operation between the two countries' small and
medium-sized businesses is in both countries' interest and the
Chinese government would like to encourage co-operation, she told
the guests, noting that entrepreneurs with vision are paying
greater attention to markets in central and western China, and
that Finish businesses should look for opportunities in that
region.
</P>
<P>
Wu expressed her hope that the Finnish government could make
more flexible loans for China and accelerate the approval
process. She said that two-way trade between China and the EU has
been perplexed by the EU's anti-dumping investigation of Chinese
products.
</P>
<P>
China appreciates Finland's opposition to levying anti-dumping
duties on Chinese products, and hopes that Finland will stick to
this, Wu said.
</P>
<P>
She also spoke about Hong Kong's economic growth after the
return to the motherland and on China's reform of state-owned
enterprises and foreign investment policy.
</P>
<P>
Norrback said that the purpose of his visit is to increase
bilateral trade and economic cooperation, and that Finnish
businesses are very interested in China, and many small and
medium-sized enterprises are already doing business in China. He
said he also welcomes Chinese investment in Finland.
</P>
<P>
He said that his country supports China's entry into the World
Trade Organization because China's presence in the organization
would benefit both the Chinese and the world economy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
