<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Shares Down for Third Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong shares were pounded
today for the third day this week, slumping by more than 700
points to close at a six-month low.
</P>
<P>
The blue-chip Hang Seng Index closed at 11,637, down 765
points, the lowest finish since April this year. The index had
already lost 630 and 567 points respectively Monday and Tuesday
following sharp falls on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
However, the market turnover amounted to 23,561 million HK
dollars (about 3,028 million U.S. dollars), up from both Tuesday's
19,260 million HK dollars (2,470 million U.S. dollars) and
Monday's 17,260 million HK dollars (2,210 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The market has been further weakened partly by selling
pressures from overseas and domestic funds managers and by
renewed currency volatility in the Asia-Pacific region, some
experts here said.
</P>
<P>
But Financial Secretary of the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region Donald Tsang urged local residents to keep calm, describing
the running fall as fraudulent buying and selling at the stock
market.
</P>
<P>
He stressed the fact that "Hong Kong remains stable, the
currency remains stable, and economic performance remains stable."
"We have the reserves of 80-odd billion U.S. dollars. We have no
debt," he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
