<HEADLINE> Conference on China's Service Industries Held in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Officials and businessmen
from China's inland areas and Hong Kong exchanged views on how to
promote the development of China's service sector at a conference
held here today.
</P>
<P>
The conference, entitled "Serving China: Prospects and
Challenges," was organized jointly by the Hong Kong Coalition of
Service Industries (HKCSI) and the Office of Tertiary industries
of the State Planning Commission of China.
</P>
<P>
Brian Stevenson, chairman of the HKCSI, said in his welcome
speech at the opening ceremony that the conference would help
develop broader and closer relationship between China's mainland
and Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
"It is particularly appropriate that we have an opportunity to
meet with the leading policy makers of the service industries of
China's mainland, to hear them talk about the development of the
vast service sector of China and to discuss opportunities ahead
for the service industries of Hong Kong and the mainland,"
Stevenson said.
</P>
<P>
He expressed his belief that through listening to and learning
from each other, the service sector and the wider economy of both
Hong Kong and the mainland will benefit.
</P>
<P>
Donald Tsang, financial secretary of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (SAR) of China, noted in his opening remarks
that the conference would provide an excellent forum for the
discussion of development potential of the mainland's service
industries and further cooperation between Hong Kong and the
mainland.
</P>
<P>
Lan Shiliang, director of the Office of Tertiary Industries
Leading Group of the State Planning Commission of China, also
delivered an opening speech at the conference.
</P>
<P>
The conference is of great significance for understanding the
current development of the service sector in the mainland and
Hong Kong, exchanging experiences in the development of service
industries, producing more cooperation opportunities between the
two sides and promoting the growth of the tertiary industries, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Topics discussed at the one-day conference included the
development of the service industries, modernization of the
financial services and expansion of the distribution industries
and information and communication services in China.  
</P>
</TEXT>
