<DOCNO> XIE19971022.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa's Controversial Health Bill Approved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 22 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's national
assembly has approved a controversial legislation which will
allow the health minister to override pharmaceutical companies'
patent rights by allowing parallel imports of cheap drugs.
</P>
<P>
The medicines and related substances control amendment bill
passed in the lower house of parliament by a vote of 201 to 71 on
Tuesday night, local media reported today.
</P>
<P>
All opposition parties except the Pan-Africanist Congress
voted against the bill, which will also legalize generic
substitution, force doctors to seek licenses to dispense
medicines, and prevent the pharmaceutical industry from offering
free samples, bulk discounts and "perverse incentives" such as
free holidays for doctors.
</P>
<P>
The bill is one of a trio of measures before parliament aimed
at transforming South Africa's health system.
</P>
<P>
The pharmaceutical industry has said it is prepared to bring
the bill to the constitutional court, and there has been
speculation that the United States may challenge it through the
World Trade Organization on the grounds that it breaches the
international trade related intellectual property agreement.
</P>
<P>
The legislation is scheduled to go to the National Council of
Provinces (upper house of parliament) for debate on November 20.
</P>
<P>
Opposition parties attacked the legislation in the Lower House
debate.
</P>
<P>
National party health spokesman Kobus Gous said the bill was
fatally flawed, and that it could bring in unsafe and potentially
lethal medicines.
</P>
<P>
"The negative signal that we have sent out to our economic
partners will soon damage the entire economy," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The ANC might have won the battle but they will certainly
lose the war."
</P>
<P>
Inkatha Freedom Party health spokesman Ruth Rabinowitz said
the bill would send negative signals to the type of high
technology companies that should contribute to South Africa's
development.
</P>
<P>
Freedom Front health spokesman Pieter Grobbelaar said while
Health Minister Nkosazana Zuma's aim of providing cheaper
medicine was praiseworthy, the bill's message would not create
confidence in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Zuma, who pushed strongly ahead with the bill, hit back at the
attacks. The pharmacy industry had maintained that drug prices in
South Africa were not higher than in other countries. If this was
true, then there would be no parallel imports, she said.
</P>
<P>
Zuma also rejected opposition claims that the bill gave her
excessive regulatory powers.
</P>
<P>
Trade and Industry Minister Alec Erwin told the National
Assembly that the whole debate was a matter of interpretation.
</P>
<P>
He said blatantly inaccurate statements had been made by some
pharmaceutical companies and their lobbyists during hearings on
the bill, and that their "excessive bluster" had prevented an
accurate understanding of what was at stake.
</P>
<P>
What was at issue was whether the exercise of a commercial
right -- in this case the provision giving the patent holder of a
drug the right to prevent imports -- should be allowed to protect
pricing policies that could have a detrimental effect on health
care.
</P>
<P>
His department had proposed that the parallel imports clause
should be invoked only in narrowly defined circumstances related
to affordability. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971022.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rural Drop-outs Resume Studies in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Some 30 female rural students
given the opportunity to continue their studies expressed their
gratitude in song today at a donation ceremony organized by
US-based P&AMP;G Corporation
</P>
<P>
The company provided the children with goose down coats, shoes
and other daily-use articles. The company is also covering all of
their education expenses for a three year program at Beijing's
Hepingli Middle School.
</P>
<P>
The drop-outs from poverty-stricken inland provinces, including
Shaanxi, Qinghai and Guizhou, have returned to school under the
Spring Bud Project.
</P>
<P>
The project, which was established in 1989 by the China
Children and Teenagers Fund, helps female drop-outs resume their
education.
</P>
<P>
The project operates in 28 provinces and has provided
assistance to over 430,000 female students.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that female students account for some two
thirds of China's total number of drop-outs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
