<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Macao Budget for 1998 to Increase: Governor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, October 22 (Xinhua) -- The budgetary expenditure of the
Macao government will rise to 10.7 billion patacas (about 1.35
billion U.S. dollars) next year, the Macao governor said.
</P>
<P>
In a press release issued by the Government Information Office,
 the governor said on Tuesday that the expenditure for 1998 will
rise 3.2 percent from the actual cost of this year and there will
be no deficit.
</P>
<P>
Most of the money will be spent on education, culture,
medicare, social affairs, security, the improvement of living
standards, infrastructure and others.
</P>
<P>
The governor expects no budget deficit because, he said, the
amount of income will increase as the tax rate on casinos will go
up from 30 percent of gross profit to 31.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
The government plans to inject 1.9 billion patacas (about 240.5
million dollars) into infrastructure construction in 1998, up 300
million patacas (about 37.97 million dollars) from last year.
</P>
<P>
The projected infrastructure projects include a bridge linking
Macao with Zhuhai City, South China's Guangdong Province, sewage
and refuse treatment plants and more welfare facilities.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
