<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK to Play Key Role in Chinese Service Sector: HK Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong has a key role to
play in helping China's inland areas develop the service sector
just as it has helped in the profound industrialization of the
mainland, a senior financial official of Hong Kong said here
today.
</P>
<P>
"We indeed have a lot to offer as a highly-developed
service-oriented economy," said Donald Tsang, financial secretary
of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) of China, in
an address at the opening ceremony of a conference on China's
service industries here today.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong has a high-quality, competent workforce apt to work
in the service sector, Tsang said at the conference co-organized
by the Hong Kong Coalition of Service Industries and the Office of
Tertiary Industries of the State Planning Commission of China.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong, a cosmopolitan city where East meets West and
information is freely accessible, serves as China's window to the
world, through which China and the rest of the world can
understand each other, Tsang said.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong is a leading financial center in the world. It is not
only the main conduit of foreign capital for the mainland, but it
itself is the mainland's largest external investor, Tsang added.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong has a very high concentration of enterprises with
considerable expertise and experience in finance, trade and other
service sectors, which can help the development of the tertiary
industries in the mainland.
</P>
<P>
Most important, Hong Kong and the mainland have very close
cultural, language and geographical ties that could not be
severed, Tsang said.
</P>
<P>
An important component of the mainland's future economic growth
is the concerted development of the tertiary industries on the one
hand and the primary and secondary industries on the other, he
noted.
</P>
<P>
"Tertiary industries, or service industries as we commonly call
them, now account for about 30 percent of the mainland's gross
domestic product (GDP). There is huge room for growth as the
mainland acquires the characteristics of middle-income market
economies," Tsang said.
</P>
<P>
Given the mainland's bright economic prospects and Hong Kong's
competitive edge, Tsang urged Hong Kong's business leaders to
seize the opportunities to tap the vast potential of the mainland
and contribute to its development.
</P>
<P>
"Our vision for the 21st century is that Hong Kong will
continue its development as a world-class, high value-added
service economy and the premier services center in the region. And
in our pursuit of that vision a lot will hinge on further
collaboration with the mainland," Tsang said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
