<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Publishes Work Program for 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Employment and euro are the
top priorities defined by the work program of the European
Commission (EC) for 1998, which was published by the EC today.
</P>
<P>
Other priorities include reforms, external relations and public
health.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission, the executive body of the 15-nation
European Union, called for a general mobilization of resources and
for concerted efforts in the coming year.
</P>
<P>
Actions will concentrate on the pursuit of a sound
macro-economic policy, completion of the single market, the
development of all union policies to take account of employment
considerations, better coordination of national employment
policies, closer linkage between employment policy and economic
policy, substantial improvement to labor markets, the fight
against social exclusion and a firmer basis for the social
dimension of Europe.
</P>
<P>
The commission, according to its work program, will fix next
spring the exchange rates between participating currencies and the
euro as the final technical preparation for the introduction of
the single currency to be launched on January 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
The commission will give special attention to Turkey, Ukraine,
Russia and the Balkans while it strengthens external relations and
prepares for enlargement that will be the main challenge in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Ten central and eastern European countries and Cyprus are
applying for full EU membership.
</P>
<P>
The improvement of public health will be one of the
commission's main activities aimed at serving the public in 1998.
This requires raising the standards of protection when products
for human consumption are placed on the market and strictly
applying rules on labeling and checking production processes.
</P>
<P>
In all, the commission is expected to present 31 new
legislative proposals focusing on the priority areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
