<HEADLINE> Macao to Have Air Traffic Coordinators in November </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, October 22 (Xinhua) -- The first group of nine local
Macao air traffic coordinators will take office in the coming
November following an eight-month training.
</P>
<P>
After they pass qualification tests at the end of training next
month, these air traffic controllers, who are all local residents,
will serve the Macao International Airport, which went into
commercial operation in November 1995.
</P>
<P>
Currently, most of the 26 controllers are from Portugal and
China's inland.
</P>
<P>
The would-be controllers have received training in such courses
as English, aviation theory, structure of aircraft,
telecommunications, navigation and climate knowledge. They will
also have to finish internship at Portuguese and Macao airports, a
report in the "Macao Daily News" said today.
</P>
<P>
The Macao airport has seen an unexpected fast business growth
this year. With the opening of the air route to Fuzhou, capital of
China's coastal Fujian Province, this weekend, weekly passenger
flights from and to the airport will reach 105.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
