<DOCNO> XIE19971022.0120 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India to Offer Gas Reserves for Private Exploration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 22 (Xinhua) -- The Indian government would
shortly offer some blocks with estimated reserves of 600 billion
cubic meters of gas to the private sector for exploration, a
senior government official said here today.
</P>
<P>
"The registered demand of natural gas is about 280 million
cubic meters a day as against the current production of 64 million
cubic meters and to meet this challenge the government has taken
bold initiatives to explore and develop coal bed methane," said
Minister of State for Petroleum and Natural Gas T. R. Baalu.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a seminar on offshore safety legislation organized
by the Directorate General of Hydrocarbons, he said a national
task force has been formed to explore gas hydrates in the offshore
areas of the country.
</P>
<P>
The estimated resource base of India is 28.5 billion tons of
hydrocarbons out of which about 6.5 billion tons have been
geologically established. About 50 percent of the country's 3.2
million square kilometer sedimentary area has been explored and
there is need to work in new and lesser explored areas as well as
increasing the intensity of exploration in the existing areas, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The country did not have any safety regulations for the
offshore operations and there is an urgent need to formulate
suitable regulations for avoiding accidents during operations in
the offshore sector, he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971022.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Captains of Collided Tankers Charged in Singapore </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, October 22 (Xinhua) -- The captains of the two oil
tankers that collided in the Singapore Straits, off the southern
part of the Singapore island, were charged in the subordinate
court here today.
</P>
<P>
Jan Sokolowski, 54, and Michael Chalkitis, 58, were charged
with reckless navigation and endangering human lives.
</P>
<P>
The two allegedly committed the offense last Wednesday night
when their vessels collided, causing about 25,000 tons of marine
fuel oil to be spilt into the sea, the worst oil spill Singapore
has ever suffered.
</P>
<P>
Sokolowski, the Polish master of the Thai-registered Orapin
Global, a very large crude carrier which carried no cargo when the
collision took place, is said to have navigated the vessel in a
rash manner and failed to take appropriate action to avoid the
collision.
</P>
<P>
Chalkitis, the Greek master of the Cyprus-flagged tanker
Evoikis, which was carrying 120,000 tons of marine fuel oil, is
alleged to have failed to reduce speed and prevent his ship from
being seriously damaged while in the territorial waters of
Singapore. He is also charged with a breach of duty.
</P>
<P>
If found guilty, Sokolowski faces a six-month jail, or a fine
of 1,000 dollars, or both, while Chalkitis faces a fine of 50,000
dollars or two years' jail, or both.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
