<DOCNO> XIE19971022.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Wants to Be Heard at Commonwealth Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria yesterday appealed to
the Commonthwealth that it deserves a chance to defend itself at
Friday's summit in Edinburgh, which is to decide on Nigeria's
membership.
</P>
<P>
"One of the fundamental principles of the Commonwealth is
respect for the sovereign rights of members and Nigeria should
not be tried in absentia," Foreign Minister Tom Ikimi was quoted
by local media as saying.
</P>
<P>
Worried that Nigeria will not be re-granted its membership,
Ikimi, in his letter to the Commonthwealth Secretary-General
Emeka Anyaoku, seemed to be appealing to the latter's patriotic
feeling.
</P>
<P>
"It will be sad and unusual to have a Secretary-General of the
Commonwealth whose country is not a member of the association,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria was suspended from the Commonwealth two year ago for
executing author Ken Saro-Wiwa and eight minority activists on
charges of murdur.
</P>
<P>
As the Commonthwealth heads of state are expected to meet in
Scotland on Friday and decide whether to re-admit Nigeria or
expel it, Ikimi said, "It is important that our country is not
discussed in Edinburgh and we will be denied the chance to
respond."
</P>
<P>
He, therefore, informed Anyaoku that arrangement have been
concluded for Nigeria's delegation to fly direct from Abuja to
Edinburgh to attend the discussion on Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Nigerian Minister of Culture and Information,
Walter Ofonagoro said Tuesday that the country's priority now is
not membership of the Commonwealth but fostering unity within the
ECOWAS (the Economic Community of West African States) and
maitaining peace on the African continent.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks while addressing newsmen after the opening
of the eighth Bauchi State festival of arts and culture. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
