<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indo-Australian Trade to Double in Five Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Trade between Australia and
India is expected to double within the next five years, Australian
High Commissioner to India Dareen Gribble said here today.
</P>
<P>
The present bilateral trade between the two countries stands at
over 2 billion Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Talking to reporters, Gribble said he was optimistic about a
substantial increase in bilateral trade as there has been a
proportional rise in exports to India of hard coking coal, wheat,
pulses and wool among other things.
</P>
<P>
"We have appreciated the tariff reduction on textile and woolen
sectors and are hopeful that the reduced government revenue
earnings as a result would be offset by increased investments from
Australia to make the raw wool available in India at a cheaper
price," he said.
</P>
<P>
Both the countries should have multi-dimensional relations on
coal, he said.
</P>
<P>
The attitude of the Australian investors and business people to
India would be gauged by the level to which the banking and
finance sectors are unfettered from interference, he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
