<HEADLINE> Mandela Leaves Cairo for Tunisia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 22 (Xinhua) -- South African President Nelson
Mandela left here this morning for Tunisia to continue his
northern Africa tour, which will also take him to the
sanction-stricken Libya.
</P>
<P>
Mandela arrived here on Monday for a three-day visit at the
start of his four-nation tour that also includes Libya, Morocco
and Tunisia.
</P>
<P>
Accompanied by four ministers, Mandela will travel by road
today to Libya, where flights are banned under U.N. sanctions for
Tripoli's refusal to surrender for trial in Britain or the
U.S. two suspects in the bombing of a Pan Am plane over Scotland
in 1988 that killed more than 300 people on board.
</P>
<P>
Mandela and Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak have reportedly
coordinated their stance on the issue. Both countries have
expressed support to a Libyan proposal on trying the two suspects
in a neutral country and having the comprehensive embargo lifted.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has failed to compel Mandela to cancel the visit to
Tripoli. South Africa's Foreign Minister Alfred Nzo told reporters
earlier that his country won't bow to U.S. pressure.
</P>
<P>
Before his departure, Mandela met with Mubarak for the third
session of talks on the Mideast peace process, African issues and
bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak and Mandela on Tuesday awarded each other with their
countries' highest medals, in appreciation of the other's
contribution to peace, freedom and development.
</P>
<P>
In an exclusive interview with the Middle East News Agency,
Mandela said his tour of the region is aimed at enhancing trade
and military cooperation together with discussing recent
developments in the region.
</P>
<P>
Mandela, on his first visit to Egypt since becoming president
in 1994, also expressed his support to the Mideast peace process
and especially the Palestinians' right to self-determination.
</P>
<P>
During the days of apartheid that ended in 1994, South Africa
was isolated from the Arab world and maintained strong links with
Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
