<HEADLINE> Egypt Rejects Proposal on New Sanctions on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Egypt has rejected a U.S.-British
proposal to impose new United Nations sanctions on Iraq, local
English-language daily The Egyptian Gazette reported today.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has delivered its official stance to the United Kingdom,
the paper quoted Sayed Kassem el-Masri, an Egyptian assistant
foreign minister, as saying.
</P>
<P>
"Egypt, while extremely concerned about Iraq's commitment to
carry out the United Nations resolutions, is keen on easing the
suffering of the Iraqi people," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, Masri received a copy of the proposal
from London during a meeting Tuesday with British envoy in Cairo
David Blutherwich.
</P>
<P>
Under the proposal drawn up by the U.S. and Britain last week,
a travel ban should be imposed on Iraqi officials for its blocking
of the U.N. arms inspections.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Washington has eased its insistence
on immediate travel bans against Iraqi officials, but the Security
Council is still divided on whether to renew the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has urged Russia, France and China, the other three
permanent Security Council members, to use their veto power to
block the U.S.-British proposal.
</P>
<P>
It slammed the U.S. and Britain for proposing the travel
sanctions to the U.N., saying that their aim is to prevent the
Security Council from discussing an end to the seven-year-old
U.N. economic sanctions on Iraq imposed for Iraqi invasion of Kuwait
in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Iraq warned that it would drop all cooperation with U.N. arms
inspectors if new sanctions were imposed on it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
