<HEADLINE> Russian Parliament Drops No-Confidence Motion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Russian Communists, the largest
faction in the lower house of parliament, today formally withdrew
a motion of no-confidence in the government.
</P>
<P>
Communist Party Leader Gennady Zyuganov told a plenary session
of the State Duma that legislators who signed a petition two weeks
ago calling for the vote had now withdrawn their signatures,
Itar-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
"Considering latest decisions taken by the president and the
government...the faction withdraws the question of no confidence,"
Zyuganov said at the session.
</P>
<P>
But Zyuganov said his faction "reserves the right to put the
issue on the agenda again if the agreement reached with the
president and the government are not fulfilled."
</P>
<P>
President Boris Yeltsin had agreed he and Prime Minister Victor
Chernomyrdin would consult regularly with the speakers of
parliament's two chambers in the so-called "Group of Four".
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin, addressing the Duma today, said he was satisfied
with the Communists' decision.
</P>
<P>
The Communist Party spearheaded the drive to hold the vote of
no-confidence, arguing that the government's budget and other
economic policies were too austere and were destroying the country.
</P>
<P>
The vote was originally planned for last week, but after
President Yeltsin promised concessions, legislators rescheduled it
for Wednesday. Yeltsin spent most the week striving to avert a
second vote attempt, and finally removed the threat in a meeting
with parliament leaders. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
