<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Boosts Spending on Films, TV Programs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Australia increased its
spending on feature films and television programs in the last
financial year, but the film expenditure was still less than the
record 1993/94 level, according to figures released today.
</P>
<P>
The figures also showed a decline in the level of Australian
government investment as a percentage of the overall figures and a
rise in Australian private investment in productions being shot
overseas.
</P>
<P>
Total Australian and overseas production for film and
television was 561 million Australian dollars (409.53 million U.S.
dollars), an increase of 62 million Australian dollars (45.26
million U.S. dollars) over 1995/96.
</P>
<P>
The 561 million Australian dollars represented 87 projects,
compared to 86 the year before, of which 33 were mainly financed
by government sources, compared to 43 in the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The figures are contained in the eighth annual National Survey
of Feature Film and Independent Television Drama Production,
released by the Australian Film Commission.
</P>
<P>
Independent Australian feature film and television drama
production soared to 366 million Australian dollars (267.20
million U.S. dollars) in 1996/97, from 297 million Australian
dollars (216.8 million U.S. dollars) in 1995/96.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
