<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971022.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Advises U.S. to Drop Textile Export Quota </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Kenya has sent a government
delegation to the United States to negotiate an end to quota
restrictions placed on Kenya's textile exports, said the Kenyan
Minister for Commerce and Industry.
</P>
<P>
Minister for Commerce and Industry Joshua Angatia told the
National Assembly Tuesday that three members of the delegation
are already there and two others left Nairobi last night, the
Daily Nation reported today.
</P>
<P>
Answering a question by John Mwaura, Member of Parliament from
Kigumo, Angatia said that some 15,000 Kenyans had lost their jobs
due to lack of a market following the imposition of the quotas
three years ago.
</P>
<P>
The minister noted that the delegation would lobby the U.S.
Congress to pass a law ending the quota restrictions and the
Kenya government was negotiating a new deal with the U.S.
government to ensure a larger share for Kenya textile products.
</P>
<P>
The quotas imposed in July 1994 has had a devastating effect
on the country's textile industry and the worst hit by the quotas
are firms operating under the Manufacturing Under Bond (MUB)
scheme.
</P>
<P>
Government sources said that about 50 firms under the MUB had
to close down and firms operating under the Export Processing
Zones had to cut their production by half after being cut off
from the lucrative U.S. market.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Ambassador to Kenya, Prodence Bushnell, said earlier
this month that she did not see why the quota could not be moved
given that Kenyan exports did not threaten the U.S. textile
interests.
</P>
<P>
She said that the issue was currently under review in the U.S.
Congress and expressed optimism a decision favouring Kenya would
be reached. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
