<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Likely to Be Affected by El Nino </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 22 (Xinhua) -- The El Nino phenomenon
could have a devastating impact on South Africa's rural
communities which do not have access to stored water and rely on
run-off from streams and rivers, a South African expert warned.
</P>
<P>
Chris Swiegers, chief engineer for the Department of Water
Affairs, told parliament in Cape Town Tuesday that the
department's latest forecasts show that the 1997/98 El Nino is
likely to be as bad as the one which occurred in 1982/83.
</P>
<P>
The impact of that event had been devastating, with rainfall
figures substantially bellow normal levels, he said.
</P>
<P>
El Nino would exert great influence on water availability,
crops, livestock and health in rural communities, as well as
South Africa's fishing industry.
</P>
<P>
The department has various plans to counter El Nino impact,
Swiegers said, but the main focus of its efforts will fall on the
country's rural areas.
</P>
<P>
This, he added, includes close monitoring of the situation in
these areas, the repair of water supply works, and pushing ahead
with the department's rural water supply program as fast as
possible.
</P>
<P>
El Nino is a phenomenon linked to the warming of surface water
in the tropical Pacific ocean. It exerts an influence on
atmospheric circulation patterns around the world, disrupting
weather patterns in many countries.
</P>
<P>
The phenomenon typically lasts 18 to 20 months and occurs
every three to eight years on average.
</P>
<P>
In South Africa, El Nino events go hand-in-hand with
below-normal rainfall in summer rainfall areas, especially during
the second half of the season. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971022.0154 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northwest China Introduces Long Distance Consultation System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, October 22 (Xinhua) -- A patient in northernmost
China's Heilongjiang Province who was suffering from serious edema
on his left leg, got help long distance over the information
superhighway at the No. 1 Hospital of Harbin Medical University,
where he had a successful operation as a result.
</P>
<P>
This was one of the first group of patients to benefit from the
hospital's new multi-media system that allows doctors from more
than 20 renowned hospitals all across the country to help with a
diagnosis.
</P>
<P>
When the patient was admitted to the hospital, his left leg was
so swollen that it was as big as his waist. Doctors consulted with
two professors at Beijing Union Hospital, who reached the decision
that the cause was filariasis, and they worked out a plan for
surgery, which proved successful.
</P>
<P>
Heilongjiang Province is now trying to build a medical
consultation network that connects more than 30 hospitals in ten
major cities, with the city of Harbin as the center.  
</P>
</TEXT>
