<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SKorea Rejects Japanese Military Operation on Its Territory </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, October 22 (Xinhua) -- South Korea will not allow the
Japanese Self-Defense Force (SDF) to operate in South Korea's
sovereign territory, though the recently revised Washington-Tokyo
defense guidelines allows Japanese troops an expanded role in case of
regional conflicts, the South Korean Defense Ministry said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Defense Ministry has also notified the U.S. and Japanese
defense authorities that they must have prior consultations with South
Korea when they work out details of new guidelines which may contain
issues related to South Korea's sovereignty, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
"We have also delivered our intention that the Japanese forces,
prior to their operations in international waters close to the South
Korea side and in the South Korea air identification zone (KADIZ),
should consult with us in advance," the ministry said in a press
release.
</P>
<P>
"We hope the new defense guidelines will not lead to revision of
Japan's constitution, which allows Japanese armed forces to engage
only defensively, and for Japanese forces to become a `projection
power' in the region," a ministry official said.
</P>
<P>
Consultations with neighboring countries are needed lest Japanese
forces' operations in the region cause tension, he said.
</P>
<P>
The revised U.S.-Japan military guidelines, which was unveiled
Sept. 23, cover bilateral security arrangements in case of an armed
attack against Japan and "in situations in areas surrounding Japan."
</P>
<P>
Analysts in Seoul express the concern that the existing South
Korea-U.S. mutual defense treaty might be reduced to a subordinate
agreement against the new U.S-Japan defense guidelines. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
