<HEADLINE> Indonesian Plane's Black Box to Be Opened </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 22 (Xinhua) -- The black box of the Indonesian
Garuda Airbus A-300 which crashed on September 26 in North Sumatra
will be opened for analysis in Australia, a senior official said.
</P>
<P>
"The box containing the cockpit data recorder was found at
around 11:40 a.m. local time on Tuesday while the flight data
recorder was found later at 15:00 p.m.," Transportation Minister
Haryanto Dhanutirto said on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
The Airbus went down in a smoggy valley at Buah Nabar Village,
Sibolangit Sub-District near Medan, capital of North Sumatra
Province, killing all 234 people on board.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the box was still in good shape and would
soon be flown to Canberra where it would be opened and analyzed.
</P>
<P>
The black box is a voice recorder which contains the entire
conversation between the pilot and airport tower officials. It is
expected to help find the cause of the accident, the worst in
Indonesia's aviation history.  
</P>
