<HEADLINE> Pilgrimage Season Begins in Tibet (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, October 22 (Xinhua) -- The old man who lay prostrate in
front of the Johkang Monastery in Lhasa, murmuring prayers, said
that he and 39 others had come from their hometown in eastern
Tibet to reaffirm their vows to Buddha.
</P>
<P>
"We prayed and offered lamp oil to the monastery, hoping that
we and our families have good health and long life, and do better
year by year," Zhaba said. The Johkang, in the center of the old
urban area of Lhasa, is worshiped by various Tibetan Buddhist
sects, and burning incense has been around for more than 1,300
years.
</P>
<P>
Pilgrimages normally begin in the middle of October and last
until the end of the following March, according to Nyima Cering,
deputy head of the monastery's Democratic Management
Committee. The slack winter season for farmers on the Tibetan
plateau has not come yet, but the incense in front of the
Monastery is burning again.
</P>
<P>
The monastery contains a life-size gold sculpture of Sakyamuni,
the founder of Buddhism that was brought to Tibet in the middle of
the seventh century by Princess Wen Cheng of the Tang Dynasty
(618-907).
</P>
<P>
Tibetans from Qinghai, Gansu, Sichuan, and Yunnan provinces,
and other areas outside Tibet come to Lhasa to pray, and a visit
to the Johkang Monastery is a must.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971022.0159 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pilgrimage Season Begins in Tibet (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"Sometimes, as many as 10,000 people worship at the monastery
in a single day," Nyima Cering said. Large numbers started coming
from early October this year.
</P>
<P>
"They come in an endless stream, giving us a lot of management
work, and many lamas don't have their meals on time," he said,
"But it is our duty to meet their religious needs to the best of
our ability." Many lamas rise early and go to sleep late in order
to find time to study Buddhist scriptures.
</P>
<P>
Nyima Cering came to the monastery ten years ago and studied at
the Chinese Buddhist College in Beijing from 1989 to 1990. The
college is the highest learning institute for Tibetan Buddhists.
</P>
<P>
"One cannot be taken as an authentic lama just by putting on
the kasaya, but must work hard at Buddhist scriptures," Nyima
Cering said. "Only in this way can one obtain the essence of
Buddhism and become a true monk."
</P>
<P>
Nyima speaks Tibetan, Han language (Chinese), and English, and
is in charge of receiving visitors. Summer is the best tourism
season in Tibet. But now, with the approaching pilgrimage season,
he and some of the 120 other lamas in the monastery are busy with
the Buddha halls and putting things in good order. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
