<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Haig Predicts Success of Jiang's Visit to U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang
Zemin's state visit to the United States next week will be
successful, former U.S. Secretary of State Alexander Haig said
today.
</P>
<P>
"I'm very optimistic over the visit of President Jiang Zemin to
the United States." said Haig in an interview with Xinhua in his
office in Washington D.C.
</P>
<P>
Haig, currently chairman of the Worldwide Associates Inc.,
noted that Jiang's week-long visit, which will begin on October
26, will be a "turning point" in the development of the relations
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The former U.S. senior official anticipated that there will be
"a cordial meeting" between Jiang and U.S. President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
Haig, who served as the U.S. secretary of state between
January, 1981 and July 1982, recalled the normalization of the
bilateral relations,
</P>
<P>
It has been a general trend the U.S. and China develop a
cooperative and friendly relationship since former President
Richard Nixon launched the normalization of the U.S.-Chinese
relations despite difficulties, Haig said.
</P>
<P>
In the past year, negotiations on resolving some differences
between the two countries also made a lot of progress, he
noted. "All these make me optimistic," he added
</P>
<P>
Haig, who has paid at least 30 visits to China since 1972,
criticized a number of special interest groups in the United
States for hindering the development of U.S.-Chinese relations.
</P>
<P>
"When they see the Soviet Union collapse, then they have to go
to look for a new enemy... But these are very short-sighted and
wrong-headed people, and they do not represent the majority of the
American people," he affirmed.
</P>
<P>
"They are the minority, they are vocal and noisy, but they
don't represent the basic attitudes of the American people, nor
the American government," Haig said.
</P>
<P>
Describing the obstacles in the U.S.-Chinese relations as "part
of the course," Haig said, "It's been always my considered view
that the two great nations ... are bound to have differences, it
will be impossible for them not to have differences."
</P>
<P>
"The question is how you deal with it," Haig said, emphasizing
that disputes cannot be settled by "intimidation" or the
"intervention of internal affairs of a friendly nation."
</P>
<P>
Haig highly commented on China's development, saying "No
country in the world has made such remarkable progress." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
