<HEADLINE> Lebanese General Deficit Falls in August </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese general deficit fell
by 3 percent in August from the previous month, to some 23
trillion Lebanese lires (about 48 million U.S. dollars), local
newspaper Beirut Times quoted a bank report as saying today.
</P>
<P>
In its September report, the Lebanese Bankers Association said
that public deficit accounted for 85.4 percent of the total
deficit while trade deficit took up the remaining 14.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
The consolidated balance sheets of the commercial banks of
Lebanon rose from about 26.9 million U.S. dollars at the end of
July to 27.3 million U.S. dollars at the end of August.
</P>
<P>
The balance of trade also increased by 14.3 percent in the
month of August, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese exports rose by 1.9 percent in that month whereas
imports drooped by 13.1 percent. The balance of payments achieved
a surplus of 800 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
According to the Bankers Association, the balance of payments
surplus will allow the Banque du Liban, the country's central
bank, to offset the deficit of the treasury for several months.
</P>
<P>
It said that the central bank had exempted commercial banks
from mandatory subscription to government's bonds, at an average
rate of 40 percent, and also refused to accept further
subscription from individuals and institutions outside Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the reserves of the commercial banks at
the Banque du Liban had finance the bulk of public deficit. The
share of commercial banks in settling the public deficit
represented 69.3 percent of the total general deficit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971022.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Much Sooner Approval for Urgent Passport Application </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Any Chinese citizen who has
urgent affairs to deal with outside the country now can obtain
police exit approval within one day, an official from the Ministry
of Public Security said here today.
</P>
<P>
The Exit-Entry Administration under the Ministry of Public
Security has issued a temporary provision which governs citizens'
passport applications.
</P>
<P>
Urgent applications will be approved within five work days,
while people with extremely pressing issues can be approved within
one day.
</P>
<P>
The provision includes seven types of emergency affairs, such
as visiting overseas patients who are in critical condition;
attending a relative's funeral or making funeral arrangements;
having urgent business affairs; students with new school terms
approaching abroad; seeing doctors in other countries or
territories; expiring foreign visas; and emergency reasons
recognized by local exit-entry agencies.
</P>
<P>
If an applicant is not instantly able to prove the emergency
with valid materials but has convincing reasons for his overseas
trip, exit-entry administrators still will consider applications
on their merits.
</P>
<P>
Previous regulations stipulated that the examination and
approval of passport applications should be completed within 30
working days.
</P>
<P>
Administrators are not allowed to overcharge passport
applicants in urgent cases, the official said.
</P>
<P>
The existing price is 105 yuan, or 12.65 U.S. dollars,
including the cost of the passport itself and a service charge.
</P>
<P>
Complaints should be directed to public security agencies at or
above the provincial level, the official said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
