<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tung Says Hong Kong Moving on With Pride, Confidence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong is moving forward with
pride and confidence after its return to its motherland on July 1,
Chief Executive of China's Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
Tung Chee-Hwa said here today.
</P>
<P>
He told a large audience at a dinner that "Pride in that we are
now reunited with the motherland .....Confidence in that we can
and will make our city an even better place going forward."
</P>
<P>
Tung said the solid promises of "the Basic Law" are the
fundamental reasons why Hong Kong people are so confident in their
ability to manage their future.
</P>
<P>
Referring to China's open-door policy, Tung said China has
undergone dramatic changes since it opened up to the outside world
in 1978. The economy has grown at a remarkable rate, averaging
some 10 percent per annum.
</P>
<P>
It is a tribute to the vitality and energy of the Chinese
people and the vision of China's leaders who have guided these
developments, Tung said.
</P>
<P>
He said he believed, "these leaders have the ability and the
acumen to steer China successfully into the 21th century."
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the recent 15th National Congress of the
Communist Party of China, Tung said it has reaffirmed the path of
China's development. "We are confident that China will be more
open and more prosperous as it enters into the 21th Century," he
added.
</P>
<P>
On Britain's presence in Hong Kong, Tung said it is one of the
largest investors there. British retailers have been particularly
successful in winning over Hong Kong's consumers.
</P>
<P>
"Many British companies use Hong Kong as a springboard to the
Chinese Mainland and the region's new consumer markets," he added.
</P>
<P>
Tung, who arrived here today, is on a three-day visit to
Britain. It is the first time for Tung to visit Britain as the
chief of Hong Kong since the island was returned to China on July
1 after 156 years of British colonial rule.
</P>
<P>
Tung's trip is aimed at strengthening the close economic and
trade ties between Hong Kong and Britain, sources said.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong is Britain's second largest export market in the
Asia-Pacific region while Britain is the leading foreign investor
in Hong Kong with investment in its manufacturing and services
sectors estimated at around 20 billion U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
