<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Motorola Catalyst in Tianjin's Entry to World Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Motorola, celebrating the 10th
anniversary of its entry into China, has announced plans to turn
its Tianjin manufacturing facility into both an Asian center and a
global source of cellular phones.
</P>
<P>
With an initial funding of 120 million U.S. dollars, the
Tianjin plant becomes Motorola's largest single project in China.
</P>
<P>
Motorola, with more than 8,000 employees and six plants in its
Tianjin operation, produces pagers, mobile phones and
semiconductor products -- mostly for China and other Asian markets.
</P>
<P>
Motorola's emphasis on local markets has brought considerable
profits to many plants, some becoming international suppliers.
</P>
<P>
"Motorola serves as a catalyst for Tianjin's participation in
the international market," said Meng Xianzhong, general engineer
of the Tianjin economic committee.
</P>
<P>
According to P.Y. Lai, president of Motorola (China)
Electronics Ltd., since the establishment of the Tianjin plant in
1993, Motorola has invested 1 billion U.S. dollars, more than 80
percent of its total investment in China of 12 billion
U.S. dollars. The China subsidiary was established in 1992, five
years after Motorola first established an office in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
"Motorola will further expand its cooperation with Tianjin, and
is confident about the prospects," Lai said.
</P>
<P>
A large-capacity, integrated-circuit wafer fabrication facility
is under construction at a cost of 720 million U.S. dollars. Upon
completion, Lai said, it will be Motorola's first sub-micro 8-inch
wafer facility outside the U.S.
</P>
<P>
Motorola's success in Tianjin has won recognition from the
government. In 1994, Motorola was listed among the top 10 foreign
investors in China in terms of both export and sales volume.
</P>
<P>
Li Ruihuan, chairman of the National Committee of the Chinese
People's Political Consultative Conference, praised the company's
cooperation with Tianjin. During a meeting earlier this year with
Robert Galvin, chairman of the Executive Committee of Motorola, Li
said the U.S. manufacturer has simultaneously produced profits and
contributed to the social welfare of the city. 
</P>
</TEXT>
