<HEADLINE> Spain Offers Arms Deal to S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Spain has offered South
Africa a 2.1-billion U.S. Dollar arms deal, which includes the
sale of corvettes, submarines and military transport aircraft,
local daily Business Day reported today.
</P>
<P>
The package also include a countertrade offer of 60 projects
for industrial cooperation and joint ventures, Spanish Industry
and Energy Minister Joan Pique was quoted as reporting.
</P>
<P>
Pique is visiting South Africa to seek support for the spanish
tender for the sale of new defense equipment to the African
country.
</P>
<P>
He said Spain will submit a 1.1 billion dollar tender for the
sale of four corvettes, two submarines, and between 12 and 20
small and medium transport aircraft.
</P>
<P>
South African parliament approved in August the defense
review, thereby giving the go-ahead for the purchase of
corvettes, helicopters, tanks, submarines and light fighter
aircraft.
</P>
<P>
In addition to Spain, Britain, France and Germany are also
vying for the contract. 
