<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> St. Sophia Church In Northeast China City Renovated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, October 22 (Xinhua) -- St. Sophia Church in the city of
Harbin has taken on a new look after recent renovation, helping
the architecture of the European-style city, which is the capital
of Heilongjiang Province.
</P>
<P>
Work on the church first started in 1907 and it suffered the
ill effects of neglect for many decades, until the city government
took on the job of repairing the structure. That job took from
July 11 to the end of August and cost 16 million yuan (about 1.93
million US dollars). Local enterprises and citizens donated 10
million yuan of that.
</P>
<P>
The church has a 7,000-sq.m. square in front, made of granite,
which opened to tourists in September, and more than 500 people
visit it daily.
</P>
<P>
According to historians, the church is a typical example of
Byzantine architecture and is the biggest Eastern Orthodox church
in the Far East. There are only four similar churches in the
world, in Istanbul, Kiev, and Moscow. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
