<DOCNO> XIE19971022.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Elder Coach Challenges Life for High Jump </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Fourteen years ago, coach Hu
Hongfei nodded his grey-hair head to answer the salute when his
disciple high jumper Zhu Jianhua cleared 2.38 meters for a world
record.
</P>
<P>
Fourteen years later, the 73-year-old man, a patient of nose
cancer, raised his shaky hand to wipe the tears off his eyelids in
a distant corner stand as his new protege Niu Jian claimed the
national title at the height of 2.29 meters.
</P>
<P>
With the gold medal around his neck, Niu Jian set his sights
upon the old man, whispering the words from the bottom of his
heart "I know it is not easy for him, an old man with few teeth
left, and I only hope to know how I can reward him in return."
</P>
<P>
Yet, the elder coach cherished his own hope and remained firm
in mind to bridge the gap of the nine centimeters between his two
proteges. "I will and I can zero the difference and even better,"
said coach Hu, "nothing can stop me but death."
</P>
<P>
Hu Hongfei is a man of confidence instead of conceit. He
devoted his life in whetting the skills of Zhu Jianhua from an
innocent child to a world-class star in 1983.
</P>
<P>
When all things went smoothly, Zhu Jianhua suffered his defeat
in the Los Angeles Olympic Games and eventually bidded farewell in
1989.
</P>
<P>
"I was 66 years old at the time, but I had to re-start my
campaign against the bar from the very beginning," recalled the
retired old man.
</P>
<P>
Misfortunes never come singly. Cancer stealthily invaded upon
his nose when Hu was remapping his training schedules. However,
he refrained himself from staying in hospital and hurried to and
fro for radiative treatment by bicycle.
</P>
<P>
Months of treatment stopped the spread of the cancer virus, but
also stripped him of hairs, eyesight and some 10-kilogram weight.
</P>
<P>
Against doctors' warning of a 50-percent prospect of recovery,
the old man challenged himself to death by strolling around the
schools and alleyways for any hopefuls of potential.
</P>
<P>
Eventually, he was rewarded with two seven-year-old boy and
girl kids.
</P>
<P>
In seven years, Hu has led the kids to shift their training
venues four times, kept cycling to the sites for a daily training
of five to six hours and even resorted to his personal account for
training equipment.
</P>
<P>
Through his scientific training, 15-year-old Cui Kai can now
clear 2.15 meters at his will while Wang Chen, with 1.89 meters in
height, also beat 1.66 meters when she was at the age of 14, Hu
said.
</P>
<P>
His efforts were not off the minds of the municipal officials
and Gong Xueping, then vice mayor, led Niu Jian to Hu's resident
house in May, 1994.
</P>
<P>
Tagged as a nut not to clear 2.10 meter barrier, Niu Jian found
his rhythm under the impetus of coach Hu, breezed over 2.24 meters
months later and conquered 2.31 meters prior to the National
Games.
</P>
<P>
Two days ago, Niu Jian won the national gold, a precious gift
for coach Hu, yet the old man kept himself busy again in his "fast
run and swift jump" theory, hoping for another world high jump
champion from China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
