<DOCNO> XIE19971022.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Analysis: Game of Money and Politics: Will Baht </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 22 (Xinhua) -- The Thai currency, baht, hit
another record low on Tuesday when it hit bottom at 38.85 against
the US dollar in the offshore market and 38.40 onshore.
</P>
<P>
It was the second record low in the past two consecutive days.
</P>
<P>
In the offshore market, it closed at 38.45/38.65, following a
low rate of 37.70 to the dollar on Monday.
</P>
<P>
In domestic trade, the baht ended 38.55/38.65, down from
37.55/37.65 at Monday's close.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that political uncertainties have been the main
factor causing the continued slide of the baht.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, Finance Minister Thanong Bidaya announced his
resignation, which will take effect when the expected cabinet
reshuffle completes.
</P>
<P>
Thanong's quit was followed by an announcement by leaders of
the six coalition government parties for all 48 cabinet members to
resign to give Prime Minister Chavalit Yongchaiyudh a free hand to
make cabinet changes.
</P>
<P>
However, while political maneuvering is under way for the
shakeup, money dealers are further concerned about the continuity
of the economic programs put in place by Finance Minister Thanong
during his four months in office.
</P>
<P>
Since the government decided to float the baht in July and seek
financial assistance from the International Monetary Fund (IMF) in
August, the country's economy has further worsened, resulting in
rising prices, massive lay-offs, firm closedown, tax increases and
shrinking value of the baht.
</P>
<P>
During the last few months, the prime minister has been under
strong pressure to resign, because of alleged mismanagement of the
economy.
</P>
<P>
The general public's confidence in the government is at a low
ebb. Demonstrations have been held during the last three days to
demand the prime minister's resignation. Government sources expect
more protesters could come from the provinces in the next few
days.
</P>
<P>
However, the cabinet reshuffle is easier said than done.
</P>
<P>
The Chart Pattana party, the second largest in the government
after the prime minister's New Aspiration, reportedly demands full
control of economic ministries, while the prime minister wants to
include more capable economic specialists in the reshuffled
cabinet to bail out the country's economy.
</P>
<P>
But, at a time of economic slump affecting almost all sectors,
it would be hard for any new minister to achieve any remarkable
accomplishment, let alone there is little time left before
parliament is dissolved, possibly in next March.
</P>
<P>
It is speculated that the prime minister may effect a major
cabinet shakeup to head a minority government.
</P>
<P>
A New Aspiration party source said the prime minister's
resignation would be the last resort and admitted that a major
cabinet reshuffle would be fraught with many difficulties.
</P>
<P>
Mark Rainake, head of trading at Asset Plus, said, "if the
current political deadlock and uncertainties continue, the baht
will go down further. It's a function of confidence and timing,
not fundamentals any more."
</P>
<P>
Pending the settling down of the political uncertainties, the
baht could weaken further. It may test the 40 level per dollar or
even go down further before it starts to rebound and settle at
around 35 to 37 to the dollar, a treasury chief at a foreign bank
said.
</P>
<P>
This prediction is echoed by Chart Thai party spokesman Somsak
Prisnananthakul, who said the baht might fall to 40 baht to the
dollar if Chavalit remains prime minister.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
