<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mobile Phone Charges Face Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 22 (Xinhua) -- China is brewing a plan to
shift from a split-charge system to a caller-paid system in its
mobile phone services, today's China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
Under the new plan, only callers of mobile phones will pay for
local talk service, although long-distance call charges will stay
unchanged. Under the current system, both the caller and the
callee pay for the use of mobile phones, 0.4 yuan (4.8 cents) for
each minute.
</P>
<P>
A draft plan submitted by the Ministry of Posts and
Telecommunications (MPT) to the State Planning Commission (SPC) is
still waiting for approval.
</P>
<P>
China Telecom under MPT, one of the country's only two mobile
communications operators, supports the new pricing system, while
the other one, China United Telecommunications Corp (China Unicom)
does not.
</P>
<P>
After the introduction of the new charging system, China
Telecom's profits are expected to decrease in the short term, but
in the long run the new charging system will attract more people
to buy mobile phones and create a bigger mobile market.
</P>
<P>
The number of subscribers exceeded 10 million this July,
compared with 3,200 in 1987. MPT predicts that China will have 30
million cellular phone subscribers by the end of the century.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
