<DOCNO> XIE19971022.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-22 06:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel, PNA Agree to Resume Full Security Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 22 (Xinhua) -- In another move to create
favorable atmosphere for advancing the Israeli-Palestinian peace
talks, Palestinian National Authority (PNA) leader Yasser Arafat and
Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai has agreed to resume
full security cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached at the Arafat-Mordechai meeting
held late Tuesday at the Erez Checkpoint between Israel and
the Gaza Strip under the auspices of American peace envoy
Dennis Ross.
</P>
<P>
Arafat said after the two-hour meeting, which focused on
Israeli demand for a tougher Palestinian fight against
terrorism, that Israel and the Palestinian side had "agreed to
cooperate on all security matters."
</P>
<P>
"We were able to review a wide range of security issues
and concerns," Arafat said. "We see a good basis here."
</P>
<P>
Mordechai reportedly presented Arafat a list of what he
said the Palestinian leader has avoided doing, including
arresting those who were responsible for carrying out terror
attacks against Israelis.
</P>
<P>
"I hope that we will be able to hold similar meetings
to advance the security needs of both sides," he said. "The
main matters which we discussed today were coordination and
integration in the field of security."
</P>
<P>
The announcement of the resumption of full security
cooperation came several weeks after low-level cooperation was
launched under the mediation of the U.S. Central Intelligence
Agency's station chief in Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
The PNA broke off peace talks, including security cooperation,
with Israel in last March when Israel started constructing a
settlement in the disputed East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Following the July 30 twin suicide bombings and the
September 4 triple suicide bombings in Jerusalem launched by
the militant Islamic Resistance Movement (Hamas) which killed 25
people, Israel has increased its demand for the PNA to launch
a tougher crackdown on the Islamic militants.
</P>
<P>
The Arafat-Mordechai meeting was another step forward in
advancing the peace negotiations, which were resumed under the
American mediation early the month after a seven-month freeze.
</P>
<P>
It was also held amid reports that Israel and the PNA
have made progress in the committee-level talks, especially on
wrapping up an agreement on opening the Gaza airport in
Dahaniya.
</P>
<P>
Ross, who arrived here Sunday on a new shuttle mission,
has held the third round of meetings with Netanyahu and
Arafat to bridge the huge gap between the sides. He is
trying to persuade Israel to agree to accept a time-out in
its settlement activities, which the PA listed as a condition
for moving forward. 
</P>
</TEXT>
