<HEADLINE> Qingdao Becomes Country's Second Largest Container Port </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Qingdao, in Shandong Province,
handled 750,000 TEUs of freight in the first nine months of
this year, according to International Business Daily.
</P>
<P>
The port is projected to handle one million TEUs for the whole
of 1997, making it China's second largest container port,
"International Business Daily" has reported.
</P>
<P>
Its handling capacity has increased at an average annual rate
of 10 million tons over the past three years, to 42nd place in
container handling capacity in the world.
</P>
<P>
The Qingdao city government has spent 2.7 billion yuan on port
construction in the 1991-95 period and earmarked 700 million yuan
for key projects and technological upgrading last year. the port
is now equipped with an electronic delivery information system
connected to 20 shipping companies around the world.
</P>
<P>
One berth is the only one in China that can accommodate the
fifth generation of container ships, the paper reported. 
</P>
</TEXT>
