<HEADLINE> Kim Young-sam Refuses Request to Quit Party </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Ruling New Korea Party (NKP)
leader Lee Hoi-chang demanded today that President Kim Young-sam
bolt from the party, but the president refused.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference held at the NKP's headquarters this
morning, Lee, also the party's presidential candidate, requested
Kim relinquish his NKP membership so that he would be able to
oversee the forthcoming election in a "fair and objective manner".
</P>
<P>
However, Kim, who handed over the NKP presidency to Lee three
weeks ago and serves as honorary party head, rejected Lee's request.
</P>
<P>
Political observers say Lee's demand is actually, by distancing
Kim from the NKP, aiming to pave the way for demanding the
prosecution launch a thorough investigation of the NKP alleged
slush fund scandal, which involves opposition presidential
candidate Kim Dae-jung.
</P>
<P>
At the conference, Lee urged the prosecution to immediately
start the investigation, stressing that "there should not be any
sanctuary left in the ruling and opposition parties in the slush
fund probe."
</P>
<P>
"I ask the prosecution to make a thorough investigation of the
suspicions involving President Kim's 1992 presidential campaign
fund and my own fund used for the NKP's presidential nomination
race in July," the judge-turned politician said.
</P>
<P>
Prosecutor general Kim Tae-joung decided Tuesday to suspend the
probe on opposition Kim Dae-jung, considering the past
circumstance of political funds and fearing possible consequent
national chaos.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the decision, the leading opposition National Congress
for New Politics (NCNP) led by Kim Dae-jung, warned on the 1992
presidential campaign fund dispute involving President Kim
Young-sam and Lee Hoi-chang's fund suspicion, as a counter-measure
against the NKP's allegation on Kim Dae-jung.
</P>
<P>
Kim Dae-jung is the leading presidential candidate in opinion
polls while Lee takes the third place, trailing far behind.
</P>
</TEXT>
