<HEADLINE> City Census to Gather Information on Non-Beijing Natives </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 22 (Xinhua) -- On Nov. 1 Beijing will begin
taking a census of its inhabitants who are not registered
permanent residents.
</P>
<P>
The census will ascertain the number of non-Beijing natives,
their distribution in various districts, occupations, educational
level and the reproduction status of women of child-bearing age.
</P>
<P>
A municipal government official in charge of the 15-day census
said in an interview with Xinhua today that the census is aimed at
providing basic facts about non-Beijing natives for policymakers.
</P>
<P>
China's population administration is based on the registration
of permanent residents.
</P>
<P>
The preliminary phase of the population study began today.
</P>
<P>
The city's census will include foreigners and people from Hong
Kong, Macao and Taiwan, but only their names and gender will be
listed.
</P>
<P>
More than 100,000 people will conduct the large-scale census.
</P>
<P>
Census-takers will have household registrations of non-Beijing
natives who have fixed dwelling places. They also will count the
number of people who do not have fixed dwelling places, including
those who stop at railway stations, airports and long-distance bus
stations during the census period.  
</P>
</TEXT>
