<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 23 Kenyans Die due to Heavy Rains </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, 22 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's weather experts has warned
that more and heavier rains are expected in two weeks although
torrential rains has claimed 23 lives since Sunday at Coast Province.
</P>
<P>
Five more deaths were reported Tuesday in Kilifi and Mombasa
districts in the country's southern area bordering the Indian
Ocean. Three people were drowned when trying to cross a stream
which had turned into a raging river. The two others died
in the freak floods.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of people have been left stranded by the washing away
of the bridge at Marere in Kwale, said reports reaching here
today.
</P>
<P>
The rains, which the meteorological department said had been
the highest recorded in the Coast Province in recent years, have
also paralysed road services in Kilifi, Tana River and Lamu
districts.
</P>
<P>
Power supply was intermittent in many parts of the Coast.
</P>
<P>
Lands and Settlement Minister Noah Katana Ngala was marooned
by floods in his Ganze constituency from last Saturday and had to
be airlifted by a helicopter on Monday.
</P>
<P>
"This is a disaster because of the loss of lives and property
being destroyed while hundreds of people have been rendered
homeless by the floods which have not been experienced here
before," said Coast Provincial Commissioner Timothy Sirma.
</P>
<P>
However, meteorological department forecasters said the death
and destruction caused by unusually heavy rain at the Coast is
just the tip of the iceberg.
</P>
<P>
Western and eastern provinces will have to prepare for similar
downpours and flooding as now wreaking havoc at the Coast, the
department warned.
</P>
<P>
The rains would climax next month and would decline by early
next year, said the department's acting director Stephen Njoroge.
</P>
<P>
The unusual rain was due to the effects of high sea surface
temperatures (simply known as El Nino) which cause changes in the
rain pattern, he noted.
</P>
<P>
The eastern African country will experience a shortage of rain
next year also due to the El Nino, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
