<HEADLINE> Ugandan Army Rescues 85 Children </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, October 21 (Xinhua) -- The Ugandan army has rescued
85 children last week from rebels retreating to southern Sudan,
The New Vision reported today.
</P>
<P>
Samuel Kawaga, Deputy Commander of the Fourth
Division, confirmed to the paper that last group of four abducted
children have been escorted to his headquarters in Gulu from
Kitgum district.
</P>
<P>
Stella Awor, a middle school student abducted by the Lord's
Resistance Army (LRA), said her task was to carry ammunition for
the rebels. She escaped from LRA ranks on October 17 and reported
to an army detachment in Kitgum.
</P>
<P>
Awor, one of the 25 students abducted in July last year from
St. Mary's college in Lacor, said the rebel threatened to kill
them if they tried to escape.
</P>
<P>
Uganda's rebel groups often abduct civilians including
children to fill their ranks.
</P>
<P>
LRA is a rebel group operating in the north and has bases in
southern Sudan with 700 to 800 members.
</P>
<P>
Joseph Kony, head of LRA, entered northern Uganda with his 250
fighters in mid-September and was trapped for a month in a vast
valley between Gulu and Kitgum districts in the north. Recent
reports said the rebel leader has penetrated to southern Sudan.
</P>
