<HEADLINE> Italy to Increase Defense Spending </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Italy's defense budget will swell
by an extra 500 billion lire (289.18 million U.S. dollars)
annually for the next three years mainly due to renegotiated
supply and maintenance contracts, Defense Minister Beniamino
Andreatta announced.
</P>
<P>
The ministry's budget for the 1998-2000 period will thus climb
from 4 trillion lire (2.31 billion dollars) to 5.5 trillion (3.18
billion dollars), at a time when the budgets of all other
ministries are being squeezed in a bid to bring the total public
spending down in line with Maastricht-imposed economic targets.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a Peace, Security and Development conference here
Monday, Andreatta estimated that savings from contract revisions
would provide 80 percent of the additional 1.5 trillion lire
(867.6 billion dollars) over the three-year period.
</P>
<P>
The remainder would come from the selling of the ministry's
property and from the Ministry of Industry, he said.
</P>
<P>
"I have already begun comparing prices of military supplies in
other countries," Andreatta said. "I want to spend where the
prices are lowest and the innovations greatest." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
