<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam's Economy Maintains Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam's economy is expected to
grow by nine percent this year.
</P>
<P>
Official newspapers here today quoted sources from the regular
meeting of the government review on the implementation of the
socio-economic development plan and the state budget.
</P>
<P>
The meeting agreed that the economy still maintained its growth
impetus with a nine percent increase in GDP, and a 4.8 percent
increase in agriculture, forestry and fisheries production.
</P>
<P>
Food production had reached 30.6 million tons a year, up by 1.4
million tons.
</P>
<P>
Export values stood at about nine billion U.S. dollars, up by
24 percent, and inflation was kept at four to five percent for the
whole year.
</P>
<P>
However, the government noted "serious difficulties and
challenges to the economy, especially the recent slow-down signs
in the growth rate, and even reductions in several sectors".
</P>
<P>
It said:"Industrial production in some localities, even in big
industrial centers such as Hanoi, Ho Chi Minh City and Da Nang,
stopped growing."
</P>
<P>
It added that the number of businesses running at losses
increased while the foreign investment flow reduced.
</P>
<P>
While a bumper crop was harvested, the price of rice had
dropped too low in some areas, causing difficulties for farmers.
</P>
<P>
Many social problems, especially corruption, illegal business
operations and social evils, had not been effectively solved.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Phan Van Khai called the government's attention
to the low quality and efficiency of the country's economy, the
poor competitiveness of domestic products on the domestic and world
markets, and the falling purchasing power of the people, as well as
increasing corruption and smuggling. 
</P>
</TEXT>
