<HEADLINE> Italy Repeats Offer to Mediate in Algerian Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Italy today repeated its offer to
mediate in the Algerian crisis, despite Algeria's protest about
foreign interference in its internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini told reporters here that
Italy "wants to begin talks with the Algerian government" to find
a solution to the crisis of terrorism in Algeria.
</P>
<P>
No end to Algeria's internal strife was in sight and the
international community had not yet found the key for resolving
the problem, Dini added.
</P>
<P>
He also called for involving non-governmental organizations in
the search for a solution.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, Dini provoked strong protests from Algerian
authorities by proposing foreign mediation in the Algerian
crisis. Algeria immediately rejected the proposal, claiming it
constituted interference in its internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
At least 89 people have been massacred in a recent series of
killings committed in Algeria since October 2.
</P>
<P>
The newest killings took place after Algerian President Liamine
Zeroual rejected a call for talks by the outlawed Islamic
Salvation Front (FIS). 
</P>
