<HEADLINE> Italian Foreign Minister Calls for Budget Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto
Dini is appealing to parliament today for an increase in his
ministry's funding.
</P>
<P>
Presenting his ministry's budget for 1998 to the Senate Foreign
Committee, Dini expressed a "strong and convincing" commitment
justifying his ministry's organization and optimizing its use of
resources.
</P>
<P>
He warned that if no new funding was made available "the
increasingly responsible role Italy will be expected to play on
the international scene" could be seriously compromised.
</P>
<P>
Dini said the ministry's budget has remained "substantially"
the same for the past ten years, even though it is required to
match Italy's growing international role in the European Union,
the United Nations and other forums.
</P>
<P>
In the 1998 budget, the foreign ministry is scheduled to
receive just over 2 trillion lire ( about 1.1 billion dollars),
the same as its 1997 budget.
</P>
<P>
Dini said he would pursue a course of reducing Italy's
consulates abroad, following the success of this plan in
Switzerland, where the number of Italian consulates has been
reduced from 22 to 13. 
</P>
</TEXT>
