<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka's Main Opposition Favors Devolution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's main opposition
party the United National Party (UNP) said in a statement
published in today's newspapers that it is for devolution of power
within the framework of an indivisible Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
"We wish to state with emphasis that the UNP has accepted and
even implemented and will support devolution of power as a means
to bring about a lasting political solution in Sri Lanka," the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
"Our party however cannot agree to any process that will lead
to the division and dismemberment of the country," it added.
</P>
<P>
The UNP, which participated in the Parliamentary Select
Committee on Constitutional Reform, said it had made several
constructive proposals with a view to strengthening the democratic
process of the country.
</P>
<P>
The party proposed to set up an executive committee system at
regional level to bring about a qualitative change in the
functioning of devolved authorities.
</P>
<P>
Other proposals include the establishment of an independent
election commission, a police commission and a public service
commission.
</P>
<P>
The UNP statement was in response to the government's intention
to present the parliament with a white paper on constitutional
reforms, which contains proposals for the establishment of a Union
of Regions with more autonomy given to local authorities in view
of ending the country's ethnic conflict.
</P>
<P>
The conflict between the majority Sinhalese people and minority
Tamil people has been going on for 14 years. The Liberation Tigers
of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) insists on having a state of their own in
the north and east. So far the bloody war has claimed 55,000 lives
and rendered many people homeless.
</P>
<P>
The support of the UNP is essential for the two-thirds majority
required for the passage of the new Constitution in the
parliament.
</P>
<P>
The UNP said that questions relating to the nature of the
state, land, police powers, finance and the unit of devolution
require further consideration.
</P>
<P>
It also expressed reservations regarding the composition of the
proposed Constitutional Council and its jurisdiction and powers.
</P>
<P>
The party insists that the constitutional reform must strictly
follow the procedure set out in the present Constitution, which
requires a two-thirds majority in the parliament and a referendum
for public approval. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
