<HEADLINE> Indian Paper Industry Faces Challenge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Cheaper imports, high input
costs and sluggishness in domestic market hit the Indian paper
industry hard, local newspaper The Observer of Business and
Politics said here today.
</P>
<P>
Paper imports have witnessed a phenomenal rise during the last
three years due to cuts in import duties. "Import duty was cut
from 65 percent to 45 percent within a span of three months in
1993-94. Subsequently, it was sliced to 40 percent in March 1995
and then to 20 percent in May 1995," said K. G. Gopal Krishnan,
chairman of Indian Paper Maker Association.
</P>
<P>
India imported 200,000 tons of paper in 1996-97, 82 percent
more than the 110,000 tons in the previous year.
</P>
<P>
In addition to high energy costs, reduced availability of raw
materials has resulted in lower production and high input costs of
the paper industry.
</P>
<P>
In view of the future domestic demand for paper, most industry
observers say there is a need for a comprehensive action plan to
revive the industry.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
