<HEADLINE> Philippine Ruling Party to Consult on Presidential </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 22 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' ruling
Lakas-NUCD party will hold a series of nationwide consultations on
November 9 to gauge the sentiments of party members for selecting
a presidential candidate for the 1998 national polls.
</P>
<P>
Nine presidential aspirants of the ruling party are expected to
sign a covenant committing their full participation and support
for the nomination process, local media reports said today.
</P>
<P>
Presidential Political Affairs Adviser Gabriel Claudio was
quoted as saying that the nationwide consultation will help
President Fidel Ramos, the ruling party's titular leader, anoint
the best standard-bearer for the party.
</P>
<P>
The covenant, to be finalized by the nine presidential
contenders and a special party committee this week, will include a
code of ethics to be followed by the nine aspirants in the
nomination process.
</P>
<P>
Claudio said whoever among the nine do not commit to
participating in and supporting the nomination and consultation
process will be automatically eliminated from the process.
</P>
<P>
Political observers here believed that the ruling party is now
busy keeping unity among the nine contenders.
</P>
<P>
Reportedly, one of the contenders, former presidential economic
adviser Emilio Osmeno, has decided to quit the governing party due
to dissatisfaction at the anointment system. He was said to join
an opposition party as its presidential bet.
</P>
<P>
Among the other contenders are former defense secretary Renato
de Villa, Speaker of the House of Representatives Jose de Venecia,
Finance Secretary Roberto de Ocampo, and Ramos' sister, Senator
Leticia Ramos Shahani.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the ruling party decided to choose its presidential
candidate earlier than the united opposition, the Fight of
Patriotic Filipino Masses party, which will announce its candidate
on November 27. 
</P>
</TEXT>
