<DOCNO> XIE19971022.0241 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Largest Outlet for CIS Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, October 22 (Xinhua) -- The Tianjin airport, 120
kilometers from Beijing, has become the largest trade outlet for
the Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS).
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the airport accommodated 2,700 charter flights between
China and nations of the former Soviet Union carrying 110,000 tons
of freight, an increase of 28 percent and 110 percent
respectively over 1995.
</P>
<P>
China-made commodities worth more than 10 million yuan (1.204
million U.S. dollars) were shipped to the CIS in 1996, accounting
for more than 70 percent of the total Chinese goods going to CIS.
</P>
<P>
The Tianjin Binhai International Airport began charter service
for the CIS in 1992 when the Civil Aviation Administration of China
transferred the task to Tianjin to alleviate Beijing's heavy air
traffic burden.
</P>
<P>
To date, about 30 CIS airlines have signed cargo transport
agreements with the airport.
</P>
<P>
To cope with the growing business, the Tianjin Branch of Air
China has invested 6 million yuan in expanding the parking areas
and building warehouses.
</P>
<P>
"Traders buying commodities in China will not only help China
increase export, but also boost local economies," said Jiang
Guodong, general manager of Air China Tianjin Branch. 
</P>
</TEXT>
