<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Panama, U.S. to Discuss Creation of Anti-Drug Center </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Panama and the United
States will start Wednesday talks for the setting up of the
Anti-Drugs Multilateral Center (ADMC) at the riversides of the
Canal of Panama, according to the government sources.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman of the Transfer Commission for the Canal said the
U.S. negotiator, Thomas McNamara is scheduled to arrive today to
meet his Panamanian counterpart Jorge Eduardo Ritter.
</P>
<P>
Under the joint plan, the ADMC will be a civil institution,
with a military body in charge of operating technological
equipment to detect airplanes flying in the isthmus area.
</P>
<P>
Oppositionists have warned that the anti-drug center would be a
hidden attempt of the U.S. government to maintain a covered
military presence in Panama as a strategic zone, passing over the
Torrijos-Carter Treaties.
</P>
<P>
The accords, subscribed by former U.S. President James Carter
and Panama's Omar Torrijos in 1997, state U.S. has until December
31, 1999, to withdraw its last soldier and to return the Canal to
Panama.
</P>
<P>
The representative of Panamanian negotiation panel said the new
round of talks is intended to reach an accord on the Anti-Drug
Center in the near future.
</P>
<P>
"We will soon be announcing whether an accord has come out",
the official said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
