<HEADLINE> Ukrainian President Blames Parliament for Economic Woes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Ukraine President Leonid Kuchma
stormed the Ukrainian Supreme Soviet with a strongly-worded
criticism during his address to the third congress of the
Federation of Ukrainian Trade Unions on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening ceremony of the three-day congress,
Kuchma warned that one of the major dangers looming over the
country is the fact that politicians are neglecting important
economic issues. He reprimanded parliament for putting economic
issues on hold, thereby delaying practical solutions to economic
problems.
</P>
<P>
"Most issues are now being considered from the view of the
forthcoming parliamentary elections," Kuchma complained.
</P>
<P>
He told the congress that he was forced to veto the Law on
Pension Reforms because its implementation would require funds
greater than the state budget itself.
</P>
<P>
"Parliamentary adoption of the law was an attempt to present me
and the government as enemies of the people," the president
claimed.
</P>
<P>
Kuchma also blamed the parliament for the slow pace of economic
reform.
</P>
<P>
To achieve successes in macro-economic policies, he said: "We
have yet to rid ourselves of the political battle between the
president and the parliament."
</P>
<P>
But he said it is unfair to deny success in certain areas of
economic development. He mentioned the slowdown of production
decline, the low inflation rate and the stabilization of the
national currency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
