<HEADLINE> Russia Worries About U.S. Laser Test </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Russian foreign ministry
spokesman Gennady Tarasov today expressed his country's increasing
worry about a recent test by the United States in which a laser
beam was aimed at a satellite.
</P>
<P>
Tarasov told a press conference that the test might trigger
an arms race in the anti-satellite field.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. military fired a powerful chemical laser at an Air
Force satellite last Friday in a test to measure the vulnerability
of American satellites to laser attack, the U.S. Defense
Department said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
It was believed to be the first laser test against a
satellite. The U.S. Army has already test fired lasers at missiles
and other objects.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Defense Secretary, William Cohen, on October 2
approved a plan to use the Mid-Infra-Red Advanced Chemical Laser
(Miracl) to illuminate the orbiting satellite which had exceeded
its useful lifetime.
</P>
<P>
Tarasov said the U.S. laser-developing plan would become the
first step to further develop anti-satellite weapons.
</P>
<P>
Russia had to carefully study U.S. research on the
anti-satellite system, and take it into account when defining its
security strategy, he said.
</P>
<P>
However, the Pentagon has repeatedly said the U.S. laser tests
against satellites would not violate any treaties and were not an
attempt to build a satellite killer weapon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971022.0253 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Congress to Consider Extending Immigration Statute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Illegal immigrants may
receive a two-week reprieve that will allow them to pay a
1,000-U.S. dollar fine and remain in the United States while
they apply for legal residence.
</P>
<P>
House Republican leaders agreed Tuesday to seek extension of an
immigration statute that expires Thursday. They must decide by
Wednesday whether to include the provision in a stopgap spending
bill Congress must pass this week to keep government operations
running.
</P>
<P>
An earlier stopgap spending bill, which expires Thursday,
included an extension of the immigration provision that raised 214
million dollars for the country's immigration service last year.
</P>
<P>
Opponents contend the statute fosters illegal immigration and
improperly rewards people who broke the law by overstaying their
visas or entered the country illegally. They also say the measure
penalizes people who apply for visas overseas and often wait years
for permission to come here.
</P>
<P>
But supporters say the provision benefits only those already in
a position to secure their green card. It also pumps much-needed
revenue into the coffers of the Immigration and Naturalization
Service.
</P>
<P>
The statute does not apply to the nation's undocumented
population of more than five million. It is targeted at those who
are eligible for legal residence, either because they're already
in line for visas or are spouses or minor children of a
U.S. citizen. Parents of adult children who are U.S. citizens can
also apply.
</P>
<P>
The Senate has approved a permanent extension, but that
approval, which was not matched on the House side, is included in
an appropriations bill that has yet to be finalized. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971022.0254 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Addresses Cases of Economic Law Violation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 22 (Xinhua) -- The State Administration for
Industry and Commerce investigated and acted on 169,700 cases of
economic law violation in the first half of the year, reported
today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
The cases involved a total value of 3.4 billion yuan (409.63
million US dollars), a growth of 14 percent over the same period
last year, a report released by the administration stated
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
In addition, 510 million yuan (61.44 million US dollars) was
confiscated from or levied in fines against the violators, an
increase of 4 percent, the report stated.
</P>
<P>
It said 7,363 of the cases were serious ones, with each case
resulting in more than 10,000 yuan (1,204 US dollar) in illegal
earnings.
</P>
<P>
About 80 percent of the reported violations involved
individuals, private businesses and collectively owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
An analysis of local statistics showed that one-third of the
cases in the first six months concerned piracy.
</P>
<P>
Together with local administrations for industry and commerce,
the State administration investigated 30,534 cases of making and
marketing counterfeit products in the first six months this
year. The value of the products totaled 630 million yuan (75.9
million US dollars), the report stated. 
</P>
</TEXT>
