<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1:30 GMT, October 22 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The U.S. government said Tuesday that it expects
a single European currency has no negative impact on the
U.S. economy or to the dollar's continued dominance of the
international financial system.
</P>
<P>
The Clinton administration endorsed preparations for a single
European currency although the U.S. government has no direct role
in preparations for the EMU.
</P>
<P>
"If the European Monetary Union works for Europe, it will work
for the United States," declared U.S. Deputy Treasury Secretary
Lawrence H. Summers. (US-EMU)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- South African President Nelson Mandela Tuesday urged
Israel to implement the agreements it signed with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Mandela, who arrived here Monday evening for a three-day visit,
has held two round of talks with Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
on the Mideast peace process, African issues and bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
In an exclusive interview with the Middle East News Agency,
Mandela expressed his country's support for the Middle East peace
process, saying that all nations have the right to struggle for
self-determination. (Egypt-Mandela-Israel)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair Tuesday met with
Tung Chee Hwa, chief executive of China's Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders had a "useful and cordial" conversation on a
wide range of subjects that are interested by both Hong Kong and
Britain, Tung told reporters after 40-minute meeting. But no
details were available.
</P>
<P>
Sources said Tung assured Blair that things had gone well in
Hong Kong since it was returned to China on July 1 after 156 years
of British colonial rule. (Britain-Hong Kong)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- Defense Secretary of State William Cohen Tuesday
told a congressional panel that the United States may have
over-estimated the costs of expanding the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
"Based on what we know now, I believe that the NATO cost
estimates will be lower than those which you receive from us in
February," Cohen told a hearing by the Senate Appropriations
Committee.
</P>
<P>
The hearing, at which Secretary of State also testified, was
designed to probe the costs to American taxpayers of admitting the
three new members next year. (US-Senate-NATO) 
</P>
</TEXT>
