<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shaanxi Invests Heavily in Infrastructure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Shaanxi Province, an inland area
in northwest China, will invest 10 billion yuan in key
infrastructure projects through 2000.
</P>
<P>
Seven of every 100 residents in Shaanxi should have access to
telephones in the next three years, 2.5 times the 1995 figure. The
number of long-distance lines should rise to 80,000, 1.5 times
the 1995 figure, said Governor Cheng Andong.
</P>
<P>
The province plans to expand the existing airports at Hanzhong
and Yulin and open an air route from Xi'An to Beijing. The
province expects to handle 6 million passengers by 2000.
</P>
<P>
The province's rich coal resources will be used to fuel large
power plants in the Shenfu coal-field and to develop
hydro-electric resources on the Hanjiang and Yellow rivers.
</P>
<P>
The projects are expected to double the generating capacity of
Shaanxi by the year 2000, Cheng said.
</P>
<P>
These projects should improve the investment climate in the
province and lead to major economic gains, Cheng said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
