<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Balance of Payments Deficit on Decrease </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 22 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' balance of
payments (BOP) deficit decreased anew to 1.2 billion U.S. dollars
as of end-September from a deficit of 1.7 billion dollars posted
as of end-August this year, a local newspaper said today.
</P>
<P>
The latest BOP deficit level was significantly better than the
revised deficit target of 2.5 billion dollars for the period, the
Business Daily said, citing data released by the central bank.
</P>
<P>
For the first nine months, the net international reserves (NIR)
level reached 8.8 billion dollars, much higher than the targeted
NIR of 7.5 billion dollars for the period.
</P>
<P>
Due to the current currency crisis plaguing the country, the
central bank completely reversed its BOP projection for the whole
1997 from a surplus of 2.9 billion dollars to a deficit of 2
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The country's BOP deficit, which surged to a high of 2.4
billion dollars as of end-July, has been shrinking since August
due to a narrowing trade deficit.
</P>
<P>
The central bank hopes to further trim down the BOP deficit by
the end of this year as overseas Filipino workers send billions of
foreign exchange remittances home for the Christmas season.
</P>
<P>
The NIR is the central bank's gross foreign exchange holdings
less its short-term foreign exchange liabilities.
</P>
<P>
The BOP, a system of accounts that covers a particular period
and records the flow of real resources between a country and the
rest of the world, is estimated based on a change in the NIR.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
