<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Private Capital Flows to Asia Expected to Rise: ADB </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Private capital flows to Asian
developing countries have surged in the past 10 years and such a
trend is expected to continue in the coming decade, according to a
report released by the Asian Development Bank (ADB) here today.
</P>
<P>
The report, "Trends in Private Capital Flows to Asian
Developing Countries," was presented to a two-day ADB Workshop on
Asian Economic Outlook, which will end here this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The report said that net capital flows into the Asian
developing countries have surged since 1987, from 23 billion U.S.
dollars in that year to 150 billion dollars in 1996, and the surge
is due entirely to sharp increases in net private capital flows.
</P>
<P>
"In 1987, the level of both private and official flows (to the
Asian developing countries) stood at around 14 billion dollars,
but by 1996 private flows had reached 136 billion dollars, or 5.2
percent of gross domestic product (GDP) (of the Asian developing
countries) while official capital flows stagnated at roughly the
1986 level," it said.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the share of private flows to the Asian
developing countries has also increased, compared to that of other
developing sub-regions, from about 40 percent of the total in 1991
to 54 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
"The rapid growth and changing composition of private capital
flows reflect the increasing financial integration of the Asian
developing countries with international markets," it said.
</P>
<P>
The report said that there is every indication that financial
integration of the Asian developing countries is expected to
broaden and deepen over the coming decade.
</P>
<P>
"Gross private flows are expected to rise significantly, with
capital flowing not only from industrial countries to the Asian
developing countries, but, increasingly, among the Asian
developing countries themselves, and from the Asian developing
countries to industrial countries," the report said.
</P>
<P>
"In the short to medium term," it said," the Asian developing
countries, in aggregate, are likely to receive increased amounts
of net private flows and these flows will cover a wider spectrum
of countries."
</P>
<P>
The report said that new policy reforms by Asian countries, the
demographic shift underway in industrial countries and innovation
and technological change in the world, which will make
policy-induced barriers less effective, will promote private
capital flows to the Asian developing countries in the coming
decade.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971022.0270 </DOCNO>
