<DOCNO> XIE19971022.0272 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> North China May Have Mild Winter This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 22 (Xinhua) -- Following 11 years of warmer
winters, North China may experience another one in the months
ahead as the mercury has so far stood at higher temperatures than usual
this autumn, according to today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
Over the past week, the mercury rose one to three degrees
Centigrade higher than it was during the corresponding period in
previous years in most parts of North and Northeast China's
provinces, a phenomenon rarely seen in autumn, weathermen said.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, Beijing's mercury reached 29.2 degrees Centigrade,
which was the highest recorded in the same period since 1940 and
uncommon for the city, which usually enjoys cool autumn days,
weathermen at the Beijing and the State meteorological
observatories confirmed yesterday.
</P>
<P>
Such highter temperatures are expected to end today, with the
invasion of a strong cold air front from West Siberia. The front
is expected to push the mercury down as much as 12 degrees
Centigrade throughout the north in the next few days.
</P>
<P>
This kind of sudden weather change is a reminder that the world
is experiencing the worst El Nino since the 1982-83 year,
weathermen said. El Nino is an unusual rise in sea surface
temperatures in the South Pacific that can often be blamed for
disasters such as floods and droughts in many areas.
</P>
<P>
"It is hard to say whether such drastic weather changes in
China are directly related to the year's El Nino, which is
affecting the world's general air circulation at the moment," said
Zhao Zhenguo, director of the Department of Climate Prediction
under the Beijing-based State Climate Center. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971022.0273 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
