<HEADLINE> New York Stocks Rally </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Stocks rallied on Wall Street
today as last week's disappointing profit data were quickly
reversed by some strong reports from IBM, Microsoft, Citicorp and
Chase Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average rose 139.00 to 8,060.44.
Combined with Monday's 74-point gain, that was more than enough to
wipe out last week's 200-point drop.
</P>
<P>
Broader indicators also repaired all or most of the remaining
damage from last week's downturn.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq composite index jumped 27.09 to 1,712.54, led by
Microsoft, which rose 6 dollars.
</P>
<P>
Advancers outnumbered decliners by more than a 2-to-1 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume totaled a heavy 581.77
million shares, up sharply from Monday's sluggish pace.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock list rose 16.67 to 972.28,
slightly more than 10 points from record terrain; and the NYSE
composite index rose 7.93 to 510.19, just 4 points away from new
highs.
</P>
<P>
The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 5.08 to 458.93,
and the small-company dominated American Stock Exchange composite
index rose 5.78 to 712.36.
</P>
<P>
IBM, which reported a 6 percent increase in its third-quarter
profits, surged more than 7 dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Dow also drew a boost from its financial services issues,
which rallied after some healthy third-quarter showings by
Citicorp, Chase Manhattan, and Wells Fargo.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
