<HEADLINE> Cohen: NATO Expansion Costs Over-estimated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Defense Secretary of State
William Cohen today told a congressional panel that the United
States may have over-estimated the costs of expanding the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
"Based on what we know now, I believe that the NATO cost
estimates will be lower than those which you receive from us in
February," Cohen told a hearing by the Senate Appropriations
Committee.
</P>
<P>
The hearing, at which Secretary of State also testified, was
designed to probe the costs to American taxpayers of admitting the
three new members next year.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. administration in February estimated that the cost of
the alliance enlargement over the next ten years would be 27 to 35
billion U.S. dollars, of which the U.S. would have to pay 1.5
billion to two billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Cohen said NATO allies were working on new estimates in
preparation for a North Atlantic Council meeting in Brussels,
Belgium, in December and the new figures would be given to
Congress before a vote next year.
</P>
<P>
For one thing, he said, the initial cost estimates were based
on taking in four new members, not three.
</P>
<P>
Albright offered a similar assurance, but she said "we will not
shortchange NATO's effectiveness" and that "the deciding factor
will be bang not buck."
</P>
<P>
The senators are concerned about the costs and have told the
administration it must first strike a cost-sharing deal with the
allies.
</P>
<P>
"The cost of enlargement must be balanced against the cost of
not enlarging. If we fail to seize this historic opportunity to
help integrate, consolidate and stabilize Central and Eastern
Europe, we may pay a much higher price later," Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the Hearing, the senators also expressed their
concern about the consequences of the expansion, for instance, it
may arouse threat from Russia.
</P>
<P>
"The debate is just beginning," Senator Patrick Leahy advised
the two Clinton administration officials. He said he was undecided
on whether to vote to approve adding the three countries.
</P>
<P>
The 16-member NATO leaders agreed to accept Poland, Hungary and
the Czech Republic as new members by 1999. The agreement needs to
be approved by a two-thirds majority of the Senate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
