<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> MasterCard Pushes Secured Electronic Commerce </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, October 21 (Xinhua) -- The MasterCard International
announced today that it has made all the necessary preparation for
the secured global electronic commercialization, which is expected
to be conducted mainly on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting of MasterCard's Electronic Commerce Advisory
Group here today, representatives of more than 30 MasterCard
member financial institutions from around the world introduced
their progress in the card-based electronic commerce.
</P>
<P>
MasterCard, one of the leading credit card issuers in the
world, completed the first Secure Electronic Transaction (SET)
deal in Denmark in late 1996. It has completed or is currently
executing SET pilot programs worldwide to meet the demand for a
"reliable, safe and convenient way" to buy and sell on the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
SET is a kind of software and protocol released in June by
major industry players, including Microsoft and IBM for Internet
commerce. It is believed to provide more secured means for online
participants in electronic commerce.
</P>
<P>
"Today, electronic commerce is poised to go mainstream," said
Steve Mott, an executive of MasterCard.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that European countries are taking the lead
in electronic bill payments. Consumers are using much fewer
checks than Americans.
</P>
<P>
But countries like Mexico and South Africa have also made big
strides in pushing electronic commerce over Internet, according
to the meeting.
</P>
<P>
MasterCard says it is now creating a global, commercially
viable network of merchants, financial institutions and
cardholders to promote the project. It also pays greater
attention to the Asian market.
</P>
<P>
China proved to be its second largest market except the U.S.,
according to Margaret O'Connor, an executive from the company's
International Communications Department. She said MasterCard entered
the Chinese market in 1986. There are now 15 million card holders
in China, who made transactions equivalent to 35 billion U.S.
dollars during the first half this year, she said.
</P>
<P>
MasterCard has 400 million credit and debit cards that are
accepted at more than 14 million merchant, cash and ATM
locations worldwide. In 1996, its gross U.S. dollar volume
generated exceeded 550 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The company is also introducing other means of payment using
chip-embedded "Smart cards", which is said to be able to store 80
times more information than a card with a magnetic stripe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971022.0287 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Opposition Party Sets Out Election Agenda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Under the motto of "innovation and
"justice", Germany's main opposition Social Democratic Party (SPD)
today set out an election agenda, pledging to bring about a "new
start" in Germany if it wins the general elections in September
next year.
</P>
<P>
Job creation, economic and social modernization and more social
justice would be the guidelines of a SPD government, said SPD
leader Oskar Lafontaine at a party congress today in the western
German city of Dortmund.
</P>
<P>
He said that it was the SPD which had the right remedy to
combat the record-high unemployment of Germany, which stood at
about 4.5 million at present.
</P>
<P>
If being elected next year, a SPD government would first of all
put forward an urgent job-creation program to help the hardest-hit
young people, Lafontaine said.
</P>
<P>
He also set a target to double Germany's investment in research
and education within five years.
</P>
<P>
After losing the last four elections to German Chancellor
Helmut Kohl's Christian Democratic Union (CDU) party, the SPD is
now eager to come back to power next year.
</P>
<P>
However, the SPD has still to make a choice between two rival
chancellor candidates: Lafontaine and Lower Saxony state premier
Gerhard Schroeder.
</P>
<P>
Kohl, who has been in office for 15 years, already announced
that he would seek an unprecedented fifth term. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
