<HEADLINE> Greece Condemns U.S. Official's Statements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Greece Tuesday condemned U.S.
State Department spokesman James Rubin for his remarks regarding
the harassment by Turkish warplanes of the aircraft carrying Greek
Defense Minister Akis Tsohatzopoulos to and from Cyprus last week.
</P>
<P>
Rubin reportedly said Monday that the Greek minister's flight
to Cyprus for military exercises was "an overflight that violated
an agreed upon Moratorium".
</P>
<P>
The U.S. State Department said later Monday that Washington had
no confirmation of the incident from an independent source and the
information it had seen was particularly alarming.
</P>
<P>
Greek government spokesman Dimitris Reppas described Rubin's
statements as "unacceptable", saying that such statements ignored
or distorted true facts.
</P>
<P>
"It is not permissible for the existing facts and evidence to
be disregarded or hushed up for reasons of expediency," he added.
</P>
<P>
Reppas regarded the second statement by the U.S. State
Department as "an about-turn" which made amends for Rubin's
initial statements.
</P>
<P>
There were many who would perhaps like to exert pressure on
Greece regarding this matter, but the Greek government had no
intention of changing its orientation because of any kind of
pressure whatsoever, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Tsohatzopoulos also criticized Rubin's statements,
saying that the credibility of the United States was diminished
with respect to its desire to take the lead in initiatives of
resolving the Cyprus problems and relations between Greece and
Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
