<HEADLINE> Mandela Urges Israel to Abide by Peace Agreements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 21 (Xinhua) -- South African President Nelson
Mandela today urged Israel to implement the agreements it signed
with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Mandela, who arrived here Monday evening for a three-day visit,
has held two round of talks with Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
on the Mideast peace process, African issues and bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
In an exclusive interview with the Middle East News Agency,
Mandela expressed his country's support for the Middle East peace
process, saying that all nations have the right to struggle for
self-determination.
</P>
<P>
"Peace will never come about unless the legitimate aspirations
of the Palestinians are realized, particularly those concerning
their right of self-determination," he said.
</P>
<P>
He called on Israel to respect the Oslo peace accords signed
four years ago and the land-for-peace formula as the basis for the
Mideast peace process, adding Africa supports the peace process.
</P>
<P>
He said that his current tour of north Africa, which also
covers Libya, Tunisia and Morocco, highlights talks on trade and
military cooperation, and the recent development of the Middle
East.
</P>
<P>
During the apartheid rule that ended in 1994, South Africa
remained isolated from the Arab world and maintained strong links
with Arab's traditional rival Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
